# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: overall-pressure-ratio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/aeronautical-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The **Airbus A300** is Airbus' first production aircraft and the world's first twin-engine, wide-body airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It was developed by *Airbus Industrie GIE*, now merged into Airbus, and manufactured from 1971 to 2007.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In September 1967, aircraft manufacturers in France, West Germany and the United Kingdom signed an initial memorandum of understanding to collaborate to develop an innovative large airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The French and West Germans reached a firm agreement on 29 May 1969, after the British withdrew from the project on 10 April 1969.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] A new collaborative aerospace company, *Airbus Industrie GIE*, was formally created on 18 December 1970 to develop and produce it.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300 prototype first flew on 28 October 1972.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The first twin-engine widebody airliner, the A300 typically seats 247 passengers in two classes over a range of 5,375 to 7,500 km (2,902 to 4,050 nmi; 3,340 to 4,660 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Initial variants are powered by General Electric CF6-50 or Pratt & Whitney JT9D turbofans and have a three-crew flight deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The improved A300-600 has a two-crew cockpit and updated CF6-80C2 or PW4000 engines; it made its first flight on 8 July 1983 and entered service later that year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300 is the basis of the smaller A310 (first flown in 1982) and was adapted in a freighter version.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Its cross section was retained for the larger four-engined A340 (1991) and the larger twin-engined A330 (1992).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It is also the basis for the oversize Beluga transport (1994).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Unlike most Airbus aircraft, it has a yoke and does not use a fly-by-wire system.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Launch customer Air France introduced the type on 23 May 1974.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] After limited demand initially, sales took off as the type was proven in early service, beginning three decades of steady orders.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It has a similar capacity to the Boeing 767-300, introduced in 1986, but lacked the 767-300ER's range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During the 1990s, the A300 became popular with cargo aircraft operators, as both passenger airliner conversions and as original builds.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Production ceased in July 2007 after 561 deliveries.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] As of December 2025, there are 209 A300 family aircraft still in commercial service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During the 1960s, European aircraft manufacturers such as Hawker Siddeley and the British Aircraft Corporation, based in the UK, and Sud Aviation of France, had ambitions to build a new 200-seat airliner for the growing civil aviation market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1965, a British government study, known as the Plowden Report, had found British aircraft production costs to be between 10% and 20% higher than American counterparts due to shorter production runs, which was in part due to the fractured European market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] To overcome this factor, the report recommended the pursuit of multinational collaborative projects between the region's leading aircraft manufacturers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] European manufacturers were keen to explore prospective programmes; the proposed 260-seat wide-body *HBN 100* between Hawker Siddeley, Nord Aviation, and Breguet Aviation being one such example.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During the mid-1960s, both Air France and American Airlines had expressed interest in a short-haul twin-engine wide-body aircraft, indicating a market demand for such an aircraft to be produced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In July 1967, during a high-profile meeting between French, German, and British ministers, an agreement was made for greater cooperation between European nations in the field of aviation technology, and "for the joint development and production of an airbus".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The word *airbus* at this point was a generic aviation term for a larger commercial aircraft, and was considered acceptable in multiple languages, including French.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Additional work included moving elements of the wings being produced in the Netherlands, and Spain producing the horizontal tail plane.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] An early design goal for the A300 that Béteille had stressed the importance of was the incorporation of a high level of technology, which would serve as a decisive advantage over prospective competitors.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] For this reason, the A300 would feature the first use of composite materials of any passenger aircraft, the leading and trailing edges of the tail fin being composed of glass fibre reinforced plastic.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Béteille opted for English as the working language for the developing aircraft, as well against using Metric instrumentation and measurements, as most airlines already had US-built aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] These decisions were partially influenced by feedback from various airlines, such as Air France and Lufthansa, as an emphasis had been placed on determining the specifics of what kind of aircraft that potential operators were seeking.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] According to Airbus, this cultural approach to market research had been crucial to the company's long-term success.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 26 September 1967, the French, West German and British governments signed a Memorandum of Understanding to start the development of the 300-seat Airbus A300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] At this point, the A300 was only the second major joint aircraft programme in Europe, the first being the Anglo-French Concorde.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Under the terms of the memorandum, the French and British were to each receive a 37.5 per cent work share on the project, while the West Germans would receive a 25 per cent share.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Sud Aviation was recognized as the lead contractor for the A300, with Hawker Siddeley being selected as the British partner company.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] At the time, the news of the announcement had been clouded by the British Government's support for the Airbus, which coincided with its refusal to back BAC's proposed competitor, the BAC 2–11, despite a preference for the latter expressed by British European Airways (BEA).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Another parameter was the requirement for a new engine to be developed by Rolls-Royce to power the proposed airliner; a derivative of the in-development Rolls-Royce RB211, the triple-spool RB207, capable of producing of 47,500 lbf (211 kN).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The programme cost was US$4.6 billion (in 1993 dollars, equivalent to $8.99 billion in 2024).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In December 1968, the French and British partner companies (Sud Aviation and Hawker Siddeley) proposed a revised configuration, the 250-seat Airbus A250.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It had been feared that the original 300-seat proposal was too large for the market, thus it had been scaled down to produce the A250.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The dimensional changes involved in the shrink reduced the length of the fuselage by 5.62 metres (18.4 ft) and the diameter by 0.8 metres (31 in), reducing the overall weight by 25 tonnes (55,000 lb).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] For increased flexibility, the cabin floor was raised so that standard LD3 freight containers could be accommodated side-by-side, allowing more cargo to be carried.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Refinements made by Hawker Siddeley to the wing's design provided for greater lift and overall performance; this gave the aircraft the ability to climb faster and attain a level cruising altitude sooner than any other passenger aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] To attract potential customers in the US market, it was decided that General Electric CF6-50 engines would power the A300 in place of the British RB207; these engines would be produced in co-operation with French firm Snecma.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] By this time, Rolls-Royce had been concentrating their efforts upon developing their RB211 turbofan engine instead and progress on the RB207's development had been slow for some time, the firm having suffered due to funding limitations, both of which had been factors in the engine switch decision.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 10 April 1969, a few months after the decision to drop the RB207 had been announced, the British government announced that they would withdraw from the Airbus venture.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In response, West Germany proposed to France that they would be willing to contribute up to 50% of the project's costs if France was prepared to do the same.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Hawker Siddeley spent £35 million of its own funds, along with a further £35 million loan from the West German government, on the machine tooling to design and produce the wings.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 29 May 1969, during the Paris Air Show, French transport minister Jean Chamant and German economics minister Karl Schiller signed an agreement officially launching the Airbus A300, the world's first twin-engine widebody airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The intention of the project was to produce an aircraft that was smaller, lighter, and more economical than its three-engine American rivals, the McDonnell Douglas DC-10 and the Lockheed L-1011 TriStar.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In order to meet Air France's demands for an aircraft larger than 250-seat A300B, it was decided to stretch the fuselage to create a new variant, designated as the A300B2, which would be offered alongside the original 250-seat A300B, henceforth referred to as the A300B1.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 3 September 1970, Air France signed a letter of intent for six A300s, marking the first order to be won for the new airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In the aftermath of the Paris Air Show agreement, it was decided that, in order to provide effective management of responsibilities, a Groupement d'intérêt économique would be established, allowing the various partners to work together on the project while remaining separate business entities.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 18 December 1970, Airbus Industrie was formally established following an agreement between Aérospatiale (the newly merged Sud Aviation and Nord Aviation) of France and the antecedents to Deutsche Aerospace of Germany, each receiving a 50 per cent stake in the newly formed company.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1971, the consortium was joined by a third full partner, the Spanish firm CASA, who received a 4.2 per cent stake, the other two members reducing their stakes to 47.9 per cent each.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1979, Britain joined the Airbus consortium via British Aerospace, which Hawker Siddeley had merged into, which acquired a 20 per cent stake in Airbus Industrie with France and Germany each reducing their stakes to 37.9 per cent.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Airbus Industrie was initially headquartered in Paris, which is where design, development, flight testing, sales, marketing, and customer support activities were centred; the headquarters was relocated to Toulouse in January 1974.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The final assembly line for the A300 was located adjacent to Toulouse Blagnac International Airport.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The manufacturing process necessitated transporting each aircraft section being produced by the partner companies scattered across Europe to this one location.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The combined use of ferries and roads was used for the assembly of the first A300, however this was time-consuming and not viewed as ideal by Felix Kracht, Airbus Industrie's production director.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Kracht's solution was to have the various A300 sections brought to Toulouse by a fleet of Boeing 377-derived Aero Spacelines Super Guppy aircraft, by which means none of the manufacturing sites were more than two hours away.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Having the sections airlifted in this manner made the A300 the first airliner to use just-in-time manufacturing techniques, and allowed each company to manufacture its sections as fully equipped, ready-to-fly assemblies.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In September 1969, construction of the first prototype A300 began.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 28 September 1972, this first prototype was unveiled to the public, it conducted its maiden flight from Toulouse–Blagnac International Airport on 28 October that year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] This maiden flight, which was performed a month ahead of schedule, lasted for one hour and 25 minutes; the captain was Max Fischl and the first officer was Bernard Ziegler, son of Henri Ziegler.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 5 February 1973, the second prototype performed its maiden flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The flight test programme, which involved a total of four aircraft, was relatively problem-free, accumulating 1,580 flight hours throughout.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In September 1973, as part of promotional efforts for the A300, the new aircraft was taken on a six-week tour around North America and South America, to demonstrate it to airline executives, pilots, and would-be customers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Amongst the consequences of this expedition, it had allegedly brought the A300 to the attention of Frank Borman, the CEO of Eastern Airlines, one of the "big four" U.S. airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 15 March 1974, type certificates were granted for the A300 from both German and French authorities, clearing the way for its entry into revenue service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 23 May 1974, Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) certification was received.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The first production model, the A300B2, entered service in 1974, followed by the A300B4 one year later.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Initially, the success of the consortium was poor, in part due to the economic consequences of the 1973 oil crisis, but by 1979 there were 81 A300 passenger liners in service with 14 airlines, alongside 133 firm orders and 88 options.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Ten years after the official launch of the A300, the company had achieved a 26 per cent market share in terms of dollar value, enabling Airbus to proceed with the development of its second aircraft, the Airbus A310.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The Airbus A300 is a wide-body medium-to-long range airliner; it has the distinction of being the first twin-engine wide-body aircraft in the world.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1977, the A300 became the first Extended Range Twin Operations (ETOPS)-compliant aircraft, due to its high performance and safety standards.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Another world-first of the A300 is the use of composite materials on a commercial aircraft, which were used on both secondary and later primary airframe structures, decreasing overall weight and improving cost-effectiveness.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Other pioneering technology included the use of centre-of-gravity control, achieved by transferring fuel between various locations across the aircraft, as first used on Concorde, and electrically signalled secondary flight controls.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300 is powered by a pair of underwing turbofan engines, either General Electric CF6 or Pratt & Whitney JT9D engines; the sole use of underwing engine pods allowed for any suitable turbofan engine to be more readily used.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Airbus partners had employed the latest technology, some of which having been derived from Concorde, on the A300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] According to Airbus, new technologies adopted for the airliner were selected principally for increased safety, operational capability, and profitability.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Upon entry into service in 1974, the A300 was a very advanced plane, which went on to influence later airliner designs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The technological highlights include advanced wings by de Havilland (later BAE Systems) with supercritical airfoil sections for economical performance and advanced aerodynamically efficient flight control surfaces.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The 5.64 m (222 in) diameter circular fuselage section allows an eight-abreast passenger seating and is wide enough for 2 LD3 cargo containers side by side.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Structures are made from metal billets, reducing weight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It is the first airliner to be fitted with wind shear protection.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Its advanced autopilots are capable of flying the aircraft from climb-out to landing, and it has an electrically controlled braking system.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Additional composites were also made use of, such as carbon-fibre-reinforced polymer (CFRP), as well as their presence in an increasing proportion of the aircraft's components, including the spoilers, rudder, air brakes, and landing gear doors.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Another feature of later aircraft was the addition of wingtip fences, which improved aerodynamic performance and thus reduced cruise fuel consumption by about 1.5% for the A300-600.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In addition to passenger duties, the A300 became widely used by air freight operators; according to Airbus, it is the best-selling freight aircraft of all time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Various variants of the A300 were built to meet customer demands, often for diverse roles such as aerial refueling tankers, freighter models (new-build and conversions), combi aircraft, military airlifter, and VIP transport.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Perhaps the most visually unique of the variants is the A300-600ST Beluga, an oversized cargo-carrying model operated by Airbus to carry aircraft sections between their manufacturing facilities.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300 was the basis for, and retained a high level of commonality with, the second airliner produced by Airbus, the smaller Airbus A310.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 23 May 1974, the first A300 entered commercial service, operating the type’s inaugural revenue flight for Air France between Paris and London.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In the years immediately following its introduction, sales of the A300 remained limited.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Most early orders came from airlines under political or industrial pressure to support domestically produced aircraft, particularly Air France and Lufthansa, which were the first two customers for the type.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During the aircraft’s development, many airlines had expressed interest in a wide-body aircraft optimized for short-haul operations.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] By the mid-1970s, however, operators found that demand on many routes was insufficient to consistently fill the larger cabins.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Airlines were often forced to reduce service frequencies in an effort to improve load factors, which in turn led to the loss of passengers to competitors operating more frequent narrow-body flights.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In addition, the A300’s twin-engine configuration initially restricted its use on many over-water routes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Following the appointment of Bernard Lathière as Henri Ziegler’s replacement in 1975, Airbus adopted a more aggressive sales strategy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Despite this, between December 1975 and May 1977 no new orders were secured.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During this period, a number of “whitetail” A300s—completed but unsold aircraft—were stored at Toulouse, and production fell to half an aircraft per month amid calls to suspend the program entirely.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] During early flight testing, Airbus held discussions with Korean Air regarding the development of a longer-range version of the A300, which would become the A300B4.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In September 1974, Korean Air placed an order for four A300B4s, with options for two additional aircraft, becoming the first non-European airline to order the type.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] This sale led Airbus to adopt what it termed the "Silk Road" strategy, identifying Southeast Asia as a key growth market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Because Asia did not have restrictions comparable to those imposed by the U.S.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Federal Aviation Administration on over-water flights by twin-engine airliners at the time, operators were able to use A300s on routes across bodies of water such as the Bay of Bengal and South China Sea.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1977, Airbus sought to break into the U.S. market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] To demonstrate the A300’s economic performance and operational suitability, Airbus provided Eastern Air Lines with four aircraft on a six-month lease at no cost, other than crew training and routine operating expenses such as fuel.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The arrangement allowed Eastern to return the aircraft at the end of the trial if it was dissatisfied with their performance.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The gamble paid off: Eastern’s chief executive officer, former Apollo program astronaut Frank Borman, stated that the A300 consumed 30 percent less fuel than the airline’s Lockheed L-1011 TriStar fleet, exceeding expectations.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Although the aircraft was larger than Eastern had originally sought, the airline concluded that it could replace its aging DC-9s and 727-100s and was capable of operating from short-runway airports while offering sufficient range for routes such as New York City–Miami.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Eager to secure its first major U.S. customer, Airbus agreed to additional concessions, including loan guarantees backed by European governments and compensation for the difference between the A300’s operating costs and those of a smaller 170-seat aircraft that Eastern had originally preferred.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Following the trial and subsequent negotiations, Eastern placed an order for 23 A300s, becoming the first U.S. airline customer for the type and marking a major breakthrough for Airbus in the American market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The Eastern order is often cited as the point at which Airbus came to be regarded as a serious competitor to the major American aircraft manufacturers Boeing and McDonnell Douglas.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The breakthrough was shortly followed by an order from Pan Am.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Another major turning point for the program came in 1977 with the adoption of ETOPS, a revised FAA rule that allowed twin-engine jets to fly long-distance routes that had previously been off-limits.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] That year, the A300B4 became the first aircraft to receive ETOPS certification.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] This enabled Airbus to market the A300 as a transatlantic airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Sales were further supported by rising oil prices, which tripled between 1978 and 1981, and the A300’s substantially lower fuel consumption compared with the tri- and quad-jet aircraft then in service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] By 1981, Airbus had grown rapidly, with more than 400 aircraft sold to over forty airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In 1982, Airbus introduced the Forward-Facing Crew Cockpit (FFCC) concept, making the A300 the world’s first wide-body aircraft certified for operation by a two-person flight crew, further improving operating economics.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Building on the FFCC concept, the new variant featured a two-crew cockpit and a number of refinements that improved efficiency, increased passenger capacity, reduced production costs, and enabled certification for 180-minute ETOPS.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] By the 1990s, the A300 was being heavily promoted as a cargo freighter, with particular interest in the secondhand market for conversion to freighters.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Freighter variants—either new-build A300-600s or converted ex-passenger A300s—account for most of the world's freighter fleet after the Boeing 747 freighter.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The largest freight operator of the A300 is FedEx Express, which had 70 aircraft in service as of September 2022, while UPS Airlines operates 52 A300 freighters.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Despite its early challenges, the A300 family ultimately achieved commercial success, with a total of 561 aircraft delivered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The program also provided Airbus with critical experience in the competitive manufacture and marketing of commercial airliners.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The basic A300 fuselage later served as the basis for several derivative aircraft, including the shortened A310, the stretched A330 and A340, and the specialized derivative *Beluga* transport.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In March 2006, Airbus announced the impending closure of the A300/A310 final assembly line, making them the first Airbus aircraft types to be discontinued.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The final production A300 was delivered to FedEx Express on 12 July 2007.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Airbus subsequently announced a support package to keep A300s in commercial service and positioned the A330-200F freighter as a replacement for the A300 cargo variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The service life of UPS Airlines’ fleet of 52 A300s, delivered between 2000 and 2006, is being extended to 2035 through a flight deck modernization program based on Honeywell Primus Epic avionics.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The upgrade includes new cockpit displays and a flight management system, improved weather radar, a central maintenance system, and an updated enhanced ground proximity warning system.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Given the fleet’s relatively light utilization of two to three cycles per day, the aircraft are not expected to reach their maximum certified cycle limits by that time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The first modification was carried out at Airbus’s Toulouse facility in 2019 and certified in 2020.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] As of July 2017, 211 A300s remained in service with 22 operators worldwide, with FedEx Express the largest operator, flying 68 A300-600F aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300B1 was the first variant to take flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It had a maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) of 132 t (291,000 lb), was 51 m (167 ft) long and was powered by two General Electric CF6-50A engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Only two prototypes of the variant were built before it was adapted into the A300B2, the first production variant of the airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The second prototype was leased to Trans European Airways in 1974.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Responding to a need for more seats from Air France, Airbus decided that the first production variant should be larger than the original prototype A300B1.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The CF6-50A powered A300B2-100 was 2.6 m (8.5 ft) longer than the A300B1 and had an increased MTOW of 137 t (302,000 lb), allowing for 30 additional seats and bringing the typical passenger count up to 281, with capacity for 20 LD3 containers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Two prototypes were built and the variant made its maiden flight on 28 June 1973, became certified on 15 March 1974 and entered service with Air France on 23 May 1974.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] For the A300B2-200, originally designated as the A300B2K, Krueger flaps were introduced at the leading-edge root, the slat angles were reduced from 20 degrees to 16 degrees, and other lift related changes were made in order to introduce a high-lift system.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] This was done to improve performance when operating at high-altitude airports, where the air is less dense and lift generation is reduced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The variant had an increased MTOW of 142 t (313,000 lb) and was powered by CF6-50C engines, was certified on 23 June 1976, and entered service with South African Airways in November 1976.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] CF6-50C1 and CF6-50C2 models were also later fitted depending on customer requirements, these became certified on 22 February 1978 and 21 February 1980 respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300B2-320 introduced the Pratt & Whitney JT9D powerplant and was powered by JT9D-59A engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It retained the 142 t (313,000 lb) MTOW of the B2-200, was certified on 4 January 1980, and entered service with Scandinavian Airlines on 18 February 1980, with only four being produced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The initial A300B4 variant, later named the A300B4-100, included a centre fuel tank for an increased fuel capacity of 47.5 tonnes (105,000 lb), and had an increased MTOW of 157.5 tonnes (347,000 lb).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It also featured Krueger flaps and had a similar high-lift system to what was later fitted to the A300B2-200.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The variant made its maiden flight on 26 December 1974, was certified on 26 March 1975, and entered service with Bavaria Germanair in December 1975.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300B4-200 had an increased MTOW of 165 tonnes (364,000 lb) and featured an additional optional fuel tank in the rear cargo hold, which would reduce the cargo capacity by two LD3 containers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The variant was certified on 26 April 1979.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300B4-200 FFCC is a variant of the A300B4-200 that eliminated the flight engineer's position while retaining analog flight instruments.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It incorporated the Forward-Facing Crew Cockpit (FFCC) concept, allowing the aircraft to be operated by a two-person flight crew.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The type was introduced into service by Garuda Indonesian Airways in 1982 and became the world’s first wide-body aircraft certified for operation without a third cockpit crew member.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Finnair, SAS Airlines, and VASP subsequently ordered and operated A300 aircraft equipped with the FFCC configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300-600, officially designated as the A300B4-600, was slightly longer than the A300B2 and A300B4 variants and had an increased interior space from using a similar rear fuselage to the Airbus A310; this allowed it to have two additional rows of seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It was initially powered by Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7R4H1 engines, but was later fitted with General Electric CF6-80C2 engines, with Pratt & Whitney PW4156 or PW4158 engines being introduced in 1986.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Other changes include an improved wing featuring a re-cambered trailing edge, the incorporation of simpler single-slotted Fowler flaps, the deletion of slat fences, and the removal of the outboard ailerons after they were deemed unnecessary on the A310.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The variant made its first flight on 8 July 1983, was certified on 9 March 1984, and entered service in June 1984 with Saudi Arabian Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] A total of 313 A300-600s (all versions) have been sold.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A300-600 uses the A310's glass cockpits, featuring digital technology and electronic displays, eliminating the need for a flight engineer.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The FAA issues a single type rating which allows operation of both the A310 and A300-600.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Airbus had demand for an aircraft smaller than the A300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 7 July 1978, the A310 (initially the A300B10) was launched with orders from Swissair and Lufthansa.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] On 3 April 1982, the first prototype conducted its maiden flight and it received its type certification on 11 March 1983.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Keeping the same eight-abreast cross-section, the A310 is 6.95 m (22.8 ft) shorter than the initial A300 variants, and has a smaller 219 m2 (2,360 sq ft) wing, down from 260 m2 (2,800 sq ft).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The A310 introduced a two-crew glass cockpit, later adopted for the A300-600 with a common type rating.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It was powered by the same GE CF6-80 or Pratt & Whitney JT9D then PW4000 turbofans.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It can seat 220 passengers in two classes, or 240 in all-economy, and can fly up to 5,150 nmi (9,540 km; 5,930 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It has overwing exits between the two main front and rear door pairs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] In April 1983, the aircraft entered revenue service with Swissair and competed with the Boeing 767–200, introduced six months before.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Its longer range and ETOPS regulations allowed it to be operated on transatlantic flights.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Until the last delivery in June 1998, 255 aircraft were produced, as it was succeeded by the larger Airbus A330-200.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] It has cargo aircraft versions, and was derived into the Airbus A310 MRTT military tanker/transport.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] Commonly referred to as the Airbus Beluga or "Airbus Super Transporter", these five airframes are used by Airbus to ferry parts between the company's disparate manufacturing facilities, thus enabling workshare distribution.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] They replaced the four Aero Spacelines Super Guppys previously used by Airbus.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] As of April 2025, there are 209 A300 family aircraft in commercial service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] The five largest operators are FedEx Express (63), UPS Airlines (52), European Air Transport Leipzig (25), Iran Air (8), and Mahan Air (8).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a300-p01] As of June 2021, the A300 has been involved in 77 occurrences including 24 hull-loss accidents causing 1133 fatalities, and 36 criminal occurrences and hijackings causing 302 fatalities.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The **Airbus A350** is a long-range, wide-body twin-engine airliner developed and produced by Airbus.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The initial A350 design, which was proposed in 2004, in response to the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, would have been a development of the Airbus A330 with composite wings, advanced winglets, and new efficient engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Due to inadequate market support, Airbus switched in 2006 to a clean-sheet extra wide body (XWB) design, powered by two Rolls-Royce Trent XWB high bypass turbofan engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The prototype first flew on 14 June 2013 from Toulouse, France.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Type certification from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) was obtained in September 2014, followed by certification from the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) two months later.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 is the first Airbus aircraft largely made of carbon-fibre-reinforced polymers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The fuselage is designed around a 3-3-3 nine-across economy cross-section, an increase from the eight-across A330/A340 2-4-2 configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] (The A350 has 3-4-3 ten-across economy seating on select aircraft.) It has a common type rating with the A330.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 15 January 2015, the first A350-900 entered service with Qatar Airways, followed by the A350-1000 on 24 February 2018 with the same launch operator.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As of May 2026, Singapore Airlines is the largest operator with 65 aircraft in its fleet, while Turkish Airlines is the largest customer with 110 aircraft on order.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] A total of 1,595 A350 family aircraft have been ordered, of which 718 units have been delivered and 717 units are in service with 38 operators.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The global A350 fleet has completed more than 2 million flights on more than 1,365 routes, transporting more than 530 million passengers with no fatalities and one hull loss in an airport-safety-related incident.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It succeeds the A340 and competes against Boeing's large long-haul twinjets, the Boeing 777, its future successor, the 777X, and the 787 Dreamliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus initially rejected Boeing's claim that the Boeing 787 Dreamliner would be a serious threat to the Airbus A330, stating that the 787 was just a reaction to the A330 and that no response was needed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] When airlines urged Airbus to provide a competitor, Airbus initially proposed the "A330-200 Lite", a derivative of the A330 featuring improved aerodynamics and engines similar to those on the 787.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The company planned to announce this version at the 2004 Farnborough Airshow, but did not proceed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 16 September 2004, Airbus president and chief executive officer Noël Forgeard confirmed the consideration of a new project during a private meeting with prospective customers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Forgeard did not give a project name, and did not state whether it would be an entirely new design or a modification of an existing product.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airline dissatisfaction with this proposal motivated Airbus to commit €4 billion to a new airliner design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 10 December 2004, Airbus' shareholders, EADS and BAE Systems, approved the "authorisation to offer" for the A350, expecting a 2010 service entry.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus then expected to win more than half of the 250-300-seat aircraft market, estimated at 3,100 aircraft overall over 20 years.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Fuel efficiency would improve by over 10% with a mostly carbon fibre reinforced polymer wing and initial General Electric GEnx-72A1 engines, before offering a choice of powerplant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It had a common fuselage cross-section with the A330 and also a new horizontal stabiliser.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 13 June 2005 at the Paris Air Show, Middle Eastern carrier Qatar Airways announced that they had placed an order for 60 A350s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In September 2006 the airline signed a memorandum of understanding with General Electric (GE) to launch the GEnx-1A-72 engine for the new airliner model.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Emirates sought a more improved design and decided against ordering the initial version of the A350.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 6 October 2005, the programme's industrial launch was announced with an estimated development cost of around €3.5 billion.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 was initially planned to be a 250 to 300-seat twin-engine wide-body aircraft derived from the existing A330's design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Under this plan, the A350 would have modified wings and new engines while sharing the A330's fuselage cross-section.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] For this design, the fuselage was to consist primarily of aluminium-lithium rather than the carbon-fibre-reinforced polymer (CFRP) fuselage on the Boeing 787.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 would see entry in two versions: the A350-800 with a 8,800 nmi (16,300 km; 10,100 mi) range with a typical passenger capacity of 253 in a three-class configuration, and the A350-900 with 7,500 nmi (13,900 km; 8,600 mi) range and a 300-seat three-class configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 was designed to be a direct competitor to the Boeing 787-9 and 777-200ER.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The original A350 design was publicly criticised by two of Airbus's largest customers, International Lease Finance Corporation (ILFC) and GE Capital Aviation Services (GECAS).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 28 March 2006, ILFC President Steven F.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Udvar-Házy urged Airbus to pursue a clean-sheet design or risk losing market share to Boeing and branded Airbus's strategy as "a Band-aid reaction to the 787", a sentiment echoed by GECAS president Henry Hubschman.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In April 2006, while reviewing bids for the Boeing 787 and A350, the CEO of Singapore Airlines (SIA) Chew Choon Seng, commented that "having gone through the trouble of designing a new wing, tail, and cockpit, [Airbus] should have gone the whole hog and designed a new fuselage".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus responded that they were considering A350 improvements to satisfy customer demands.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] One such proposal, known internally as "1d", formed the basis of the A350 redesign.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 14 July 2006, during the Farnborough International Airshow, the redesigned aircraft was designated "A350 XWB" (Xtra-Wide-Body).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Within four days, Singapore Airlines agreed to order 20 A350 XWBs with options for another 20 A350 XWBs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The proposed A350 was a new design, including a wider fuselage cross-section, allowing seating arrangements ranging from an eight-across low-density premium economy layout to a ten-across high-density seating configuration for a maximum seating capacity of 440–475 depending on variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A330 and previous iterations of the A350 would only be able to accommodate a maximum of eight seats per row.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The 787 is typically configured for nine seats per row.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The 777 accommodates nine or ten seats per row, with more than half of recent 777s being configured in a ten-across layout that will come standard on the 777X.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 cabin is 12.7 cm (5.0 in) wider at the eye level of a seated passenger than the 787's cabin, and 28 cm (11 in) narrower than the Boeing 777's cabin (see the Wide-body aircraft comparison of cabin widths and seating).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The redesigned composite fuselage allows for higher cabin pressure and humidity, and lower maintenance costs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 1 December 2006, the Airbus board of directors approved the industrial launch of the A350-800, -900, and -1000 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The delayed launch decision was a result of delays to the Airbus A380 and discussions on how to fund development.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] EADS CEO Thomas Enders stated that the A350 programme was not a certainty, citing EADS/Airbus's stretched resources.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] However, it was decided programme costs are to be borne mainly from cash-flow.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] First delivery for the A350-900 was scheduled for mid-2013, with the -800 and -1000 following on 12 and 24 months later, respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] New technical details of the A350 XWB were revealed at a press conference in December 2006.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Chief operating officer, John Leahy indicated existing A350 contracts were being re-negotiated due to price increases compared to the original A350s contracted.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 4 January 2007, Pegasus Aviation Finance Company placed the first firm order for the A350 XWB with an order for two aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The design change imposed a two-year delay into the original timetable and increased development costs from US$5.5 billion (€5.3 billion) to approximately US$10 billion (€9.7 billion).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] *Reuters* estimated the A350's total development cost at US$15 billion (€12 billion or £10 billion).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The original mid-2013 delivery date of the A350 was changed, as a longer than anticipated development forced Airbus to delay the final assembly and first flight of the aircraft to the third quarter of 2012 and second quarter of 2013 respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As a result, the flight test schedule was compressed from the original 15 months to 12 months.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] A350 programme chief Didier Evrard stressed that delays only affected the A350-900 while the -800 and -1000 schedules remained unchanged.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus' 2019 earnings report indicated the A350 programme had broken even that year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus suggested Boeing's use of composite materials for the 787 fuselage was premature, and that the new A350 XWB was to feature carbon fibre panels only for the main fuselage skin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] However, after facing criticism for maintenance costs, Airbus confirmed in early September 2007 that it would also use carbon fibre for fuselage frames.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The composite frames would feature aluminium strips to ensure the electrical continuity of the fuselage, for dissipating lightning strikes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus used a full mock up fuselage to develop the wiring, a different approach from the A380, on which the wiring was all done on computers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2006, Airbus confirmed development of a full bleed air system on the A350, as opposed to the 787's bleedless configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Rolls-Royce agreed with Airbus to supply a new variant of the Trent turbofan engine for the A350 XWB, named *Trent XWB*.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2010, after low-speed wind tunnel tests, Airbus finalised the static thrust at sea level for all three proposed variants to the 74,000–94,000 lbf (330–420 kN) range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] GE stated it would not offer the GP7000 engine on the aircraft, and that previous contracts for the GEnx on the original A350 did not apply to the XWB.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Engine Alliance partner Pratt & Whitney seemed to be unaligned with GE on this, having publicly stated that it was looking at an advanced derivative of the GP7000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In April 2007, former Airbus CEO Louis Gallois held direct talks with GE management over developing a GEnx variant for the A350 XWB.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In June 2007, John Leahy indicated that the A350 XWB would not feature the GEnx engine, saying that Airbus wanted GE to offer a more efficient version for the airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Since then, the largest GE engines operators, which include Emirates, US Airways, Hawaiian Airlines and ILFC have selected the Trent XWB for their A350 orders.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In May 2009, GE said that if it were to reach a deal with Airbus to offer the current 787-optimised GEnx for the A350, it would only power the -800 and -900 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] GE believed it could offer a product that outperforms the Trent 1000 and Trent XWB, but was reluctant to support an aircraft competing directly with its GE90-115B-powered 777 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In January 2008, French-based Thales Group won a US$2.9 billion (€2 billion) 20-year contract to supply avionics and navigation equipment for the A350 XWB, beating Honeywell and Rockwell Collins.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] US-based Rockwell Collins and Moog Inc. were chosen to supply the horizontal stabiliser actuator and primary flight control actuation, respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The flight management system incorporated several new safety features.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Regarding cabin ergonomics and entertainment, in 2006 Airbus signed a firm contract with BMW for development of an interior concept for the original A350.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 4 February 2010, Airbus signed a contract with Panasonic Avionics Corporation to deliver in-flight entertainment and communication (IFEC) systems for the Airbus A350 XWB.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2008, Airbus planned to start cabin furnishing early in parallel with final assembly to cut production time in half.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 XWB production programme sees extensive international collaboration and investments in new facilities: Airbus constructed 10 new factories in Western Europe and the US, with extensions carried out on three further sites.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Among the new buildings was a £570 million (US$760 million or €745 million) composite facility in Broughton, Wales, which would be responsible for the wings.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In June 2009, the National Assembly for Wales announced provision of a £28 million grant to provide a training centre, production jobs and money toward the new production centre.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus manufactured the first structural component in December 2009.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Production of the first fuselage barrel began in late 2010 at its production plant in Illescas, Spain.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Construction of the first A350-900 centre wingbox was set to start in August 2010.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The new composite rudder plant in China opened in early 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The forward fuselage of the first A350 was delivered to the final assembly plant in Toulouse on 29 December 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Final assembly of the first A350 static test model was started on 5 April 2012.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Final assembly of the first prototype A350 was completed in December 2012.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The production rate was expected to rise from three aircraft per month in early 2015 to five at the end of 2015, and would ramp to ten aircraft per month by 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2015, 17 planes would be delivered and the initial dispatch reliability was 98%.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus announced plans to increase its production rate from 10 monthly in 2018 to 13 monthly from 2019 and six A330 are produced monthly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Around 90 deliveries were expected for 2018, with 15% or ≈14 units being A350-1000 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] That year, 93 aircraft were delivered, three more than expected.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2019, Airbus delivered 112 A350s (87 A350-900s and 25 A350-1000s) at a rate of 10 per month, and were going to keep the rate around nine to 10 per month, to reflect softer demand for widebodies, as the backlog reached 579 − or 5.2 years of production at a constant rate.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the decrease of A350 production from 9.5 per month to six per month, since April 2020.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] After the pandemic a ramp-up is planned, aiming to reach a rate of 9 per month by the end of 2025.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As the pre-pandemic rate of 10 monthly is aimed for by 2026, by April 2024 Airbus was planning a 12-monthly production rate by 2028 after securing 281 net orders in 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The first Trent engine test was made on 14 June 2010.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The Trent XWB's flight test programme began use on the A380 development aircraft in early 2011, ahead of engine certification in late 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 2 June 2013, the Trent XWB engines were powered up on the A350 for the first time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus confirmed that the flight test programme would last 12 months and use five test aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350's maiden flight took place on 14 June 2013 from the Toulouse–Blagnac Airport.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus's chief test pilot said, "it just seemed really happy in the air...all the things we were testing had no major issues at all".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It flew for four hours, reaching Mach 0.8 at 25,000 feet after retracting the landing gear and starting a 2,500 h flight test campaign.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Costs for developing the aircraft were estimated at €11 billion (US$15 billion or £9.5 billion) in June 2013.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] 2 underwent two and a half weeks of climatic tests in the unique McKinley Climatic Laboratory at Eglin Air Force Base, Florida, in May 2014, and was subjected to multiple climatic and humidity settings from 45 °C (113 °F) to −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 received type certification from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) on 30 September 2014.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 15 October 2014, EASA approved the A350-900 for ETOPS (Extended-range Twin-engine Operations Performance Standards) 370, allowing it to fly more than six hours on one engine and making it the first airliner to be approved for "ETOPS Beyond 180 minutes" before entry into service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Later that month Airbus received regulatory approval for a Common Type Rating for pilot training between the A350 XWB and A330.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 12 November 2014, the A350 received certification from the FAA.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 1 August 2017, the EASA issued an airworthiness directive mandating operators to power cycle (reset) early A350-900s before 149 hours of continuous power-on time, reissued in July 2019.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In June 2011, the A350-900 was scheduled to enter service in the first half of 2014, with the -800 to enter service in mid-2016, and the -1000 in 2017.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In July 2012, Airbus delayed the -900's introduction by three months to the second half of 2014.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The delivery to launch customer Qatar Airways took place on 22 December 2014.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The first commercial flight was made on 15 January 2015 between Doha and Frankfurt.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The first A350-1000 was assembled in 2016 and had its first flight on 24 November 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The aircraft was then delivered on 20 February 2018 to Qatar Airways, which had also been the launch operator of the -900. and entered the commercial service with a flight from Doha to London on 24 February 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The 60.45 m (198.3 ft)-long A350-800 was designed to seat 276 passengers in a typical three-class configuration with a range of 15,270 kilometres (8,245 nmi; 9,488 mi) with an MTOW of 259 tonnes (571,000 lb).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In January 2010, Airbus opted to develop the -800 as a shrink of the baseline -900 to simplify development and increase its payload by 3 tonnes (6,600 lb) or its range by 460 kilometres (250 nmi; 290 mi), but this led to a fuel burn penalty of "a couple of percent", according to John Leahy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The previously planned optimisation to the structure and landing gear was not beneficial enough against better commonality and maximum takeoff weight increase by 11t from 248t.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The −800's fuselage is 10 frames shorter (six forward and four aft of wing) than the −900 aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It was designed to supplement the Airbus A330-200 long-range twin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus planned to decrease structural weight in the -800 as development continued, which should have been around airframe 20.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] While its backlog reached 182 in mid-2008, it diminished since 2010 as customers switched to the larger -900.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] After launching the Airbus A330neo at the 2014 Farnborough Airshow, Airbus dropped the A350-800, with its CEO Fabrice Brégier saying "I believe all of our customers will either convert to the A350-900 or the A330neo".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] He later confirmed at a September 2014 press conference that development of the A350-800 had been "cancelled".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] There were 16 orders left for the -800 since Yemenia switched to the -900 and Hawaiian Airlines moved to the A330neo in December 2014: eight for Aeroflot and eight for Asiana Airlines, both also having orders for the -900.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In January 2017, Aeroflot and Airbus announced the cancellation of its -800 order, leaving Asiana Airlines as the only customer for the variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] After the negotiation between Airbus and Asiana Airlines, Asiana converted orders of eight A350-800s and one A350-1000 to nine A350-900s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2011, Airbus redesigned the A350-1000 with higher weights and a more powerful engine variant to provide more range for trans-Pacific operations.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This boosted its appeal to Cathay Pacific and Singapore Airlines, who were committed to purchase 20 Boeing 777-9s, and to United Airlines, which was considering Boeing 777-300ERs to replace its 747-400s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Emirates was disappointed with the changes and cancelled its order for 50 A350-900s and 20 A350-1000s, instead of changing the whole order to the larger variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Assembly of the first fuselage major components started in September 2015.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In February 2016, final assembly started at the A350 Final Assembly Line in Toulouse.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Three flight test aircraft were planned, with entry into service scheduled for mid-2017.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The first aircraft completed its body join on 15 April 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Its maiden flight took place on 24 November 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus then completed functional and reliability testing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Type Certification was awarded by EASA on 21 November 2017, along FAA certification.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The first serial unit was on the final assembly line in early December.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] After its maiden flight on 7 December 2017, delivery to launch customer Qatar Airways slipped to early 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The delay was due to issues with the business class seat installation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It was delivered on 20 February 2018 and entered commercial service on Qatar Airways' Doha to London Heathrow route on 24 February 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus has explored the possibility of a further stretch offering 45 more seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This variant was to be a replacement for the 747-400, tentatively called the A350-8000, -2000 or -1100.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] At the June 2016 Airbus Innovation Days, chief commercial officer John Leahy was concerned about the size of a 400-seat market besides the Boeing 747-8 and the 777-9 and chief executive Fabrice Brégier feared such an aircraft could cannibalise demand for the -1000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The potential 79 m-long (258 ft) aeroplane was competing against a hypothetical 777-10 for Singapore Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] At the 2017 Paris Air Show, the concept was shelved for lacking market appeal and in January 2018 Brégier focused on enhancing the A350-900/1000 to capture potential before 2022/2023, when it would be possible to stretch the A350 with a new engine generation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The wing twist is being changed for the wider, optimised spanload pressure distribution, and will be used for the Singapore Airlines A350-900ULR in 2018 before spreading to other variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 26 June 2018, Iberia was the first to receive the upgraded -900, with a 280 t (620,000 lb) MTOW version for an 8,200 nmi (15,200 km; 9,400 mi) range with 325 passengers in three classes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This eventually became a standard package for all the A350-900 airframes starting from **MSN 216**.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] By April 2019, Airbus was testing a hybrid laminar flow control (HLFC) on the leading edge of an A350 prototype vertical stabiliser, with passive suction similar to the boundary layer control on the Boeing 787-9 tail, but unlike the natural laminar flow BLADE, within the same EU Clean Sky programme.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Starting with **MSN 316**, every A350-900 and A350-1000 produced had the side slip angle (SSA) probe removed after a software update to prove these sensors are not needed anymore for redundancy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] There was also a new light-emitting diode (LED) lighting package installed, replacing the old high-intensity discharge (HID) lamps; these new light units have a longer life cycle, improving reliability performance.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In June 2019, Airbus delivered the first A350 equipped with the improvement package to Singapore Airlines (9V-SHH).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 30 September 2022, an improved new production standard (**NPS**) was announced, it will apply to A359/A35K airframes starting from **MSN 579**, which is an A350-900 airframe that was delivered to Iberia.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The NPS includes a 1.2 t (2,600 lb) weight reduction and a 3 t (6,600 lb) MTOW increase, along with a wider interior cabin to offer 30 additional seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It offers the customers with a new weight variant **WV020** for the 283 t MTOW.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The interior changes include moving the cockpit wall forward, moving the aft pressure bulkhead one frame further aft and resculpting the sidewalls to allow ten-across 17 in (430 mm) seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] There are also improvements to the aircraft's take off performance by introducing software evolutions which regulate the slat and flap positions, and has also implemented a faster landing gear retraction cycle – conferring greater obstacle clearance and reduced aerodynamic drag.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] By November 2018, Airbus was hiring in Toulouse and Madrid to develop a re-engined A350neo.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Although its launch is not guaranteed, it would be delivered in the mid-2020s, after the A321XLR and a stretched A320neo "plus", potentially competing with the Boeing New Midsize Airplane.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Service entry would be determined by ultra-high bypass ratio engine developments pursued by Pratt & Whitney, testing its Geared Turbofan upgrade; Safran Aircraft Engines, ground testing a demonstrator from 2021; and Rolls-Royce, targeting a 2025 Ultrafan service entry.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The production target is a monthly rate of 20 A350neos, up from 10.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In November 2019, General Electric was offering an advanced GEnx-1 variant with a bleed air system and improvements from the GE9X, developed for the delayed Boeing 777X, to power a proposed A350neo from the mid-2020s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2021, Rolls Royce signed an exclusive deal to supply A350-900 engines until 2030, following previous similar commitments for the A350-1000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus expected 10% lower airframe maintenance compared with the original A350 design and 14% lower empty seat weight than the Boeing 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Design freeze for the A350-900 was achieved in December 2008.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350's competitor, the Boeing 787, is 50% composites, 20% aluminium, 15% titanium, 10% steel, and 5% other.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 features a new composite fuselage with a constant width from door 1 to door 4, unlike previous Airbus aircraft, to provide maximum usable volume.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The double-lobe (ovoid) fuselage cross-section has a maximum outer diameter of 5.97 m (19.6 ft), compared to 5.64 m (18.5 ft) for the A330/A340.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The cabin's internal width is 5.61 m (18.4 ft) at armrest level compared to 5.49 m (18.0 ft) in the Boeing 787 and 5.87 m (19.3 ft) in the Boeing 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It allows for an eight-across 2–4–2 arrangement in a premium economy layout, with the seats being 49.5 cm (19.5 in) wide between 5 cm (2.0 in) wide arm rests.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus states that the seat will be 1.3 cm (0.5 in) wider than a 787 seat in the equivalent configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In the nine-across, 3–3–3 standard economy layout, the A350 seat will be 45 cm (18 in) wide, 1.27 cm (0.5 in) wider than a seat in the equivalent layout in the 787, and 3.9 cm (1.5 in) wider than a seat in the equivalent A330 layout.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The current 777 and future derivatives have 1.27 cm (0.5 in) greater seat width than the A350 in a nine-across configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The 10-across seating on the A350 is similar to a 9-across configuration on the A330, with a seat width of 41.65 cm (16.4 in).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Overall, the A350 gives passengers more headroom, larger overhead storage space, and wider panoramic windows than current Airbus models.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 nose section has a configuration derived from the A380 with a forward-mounted nosegear bay and a six-panel flightdeck windscreen.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This differs substantially from the four-window arrangement in the original A350 XWB design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The new nose, made of aluminium, improves aerodynamics and enables overhead crew rest areas to be installed further forward and eliminate any encroachment in the passenger cabin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The new windscreen has been revised to improve vision by reducing the width of the centre post.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The upper shell radius of the nose section has been increased.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The Airbus A350 initially featured manual window shades.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2020, Airbus announced that dimmable windows, similar to those on the Boeing 787, would be offered as an option.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] These windows are designed to darken or lighten more efficiently, providing greater control over light levels while maintaining an outside view.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Starlux Airlines became the first carrier to receive A350s equipped with dimmable windows across all cabins, while Japan Airlines offers this feature exclusively in premium economy and higher-class cabins, retaining manual shades for economy passengers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350 features new composite wings with a wingspan that is common to the proposed variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Its 64.75 m (212.4 ft) wingspan stays within the same ICAO Aerodrome Reference Code E 65 m limit as the A330/A340 and the Boeing 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350's wing has a 31.9° sweep angle for a Mach 0.85 cruise speed and has a maximum operating speed of Mach 0.89.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This is between the 436.8 m2 (4,702 sq ft) wing of the current Boeing 777-200LR/300ER and the 466.8 m2 (5,025 sq ft) wing of the in-development Boeing 777X.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] However, Boeing and Airbus do not use the same measurement.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350-1000 wing is 22.3 m2 (240 ft2) larger through a 30 cm (12 in) extension to the inboard sections of the fixed trailing edge.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] A new trailing-edge high-lift device has been adopted with an advanced dropped-hinge flap similar to that of the A380, which permits the gap between the trailing edge and the flap to be closed with the spoiler.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The manufacturer has extensively used computational fluid dynamics and also carried out more than 4,000 hours of low- and high-speed windtunnel testing to refine the aerodynamic design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The final configuration of wing and winglet was achieved for the "Maturity Gate 5" on 17 December 2008.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The wingtip device curves upwards over the final 4.4 m (14 ft).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The wings are produced in the new £400 million (US$641M), 46,000 m2 (500,000 sq ft) North Factory at Airbus Broughton, employing 650 workers, in a specialist facility constructed with £29M of support from the Welsh Government.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus adopted a new philosophy for the attachment of the A350's main undercarriage as part of the switch to a composite wing structure.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Each main undercarriage leg is attached to the rear wing spar forward and to a gear beam aft, which itself is attached to the wing and the fuselage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] To help reduce the loads further into the wing, a double side-stay configuration has been adopted.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This solution resembles the design of the Vickers VC10.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus devised a three-pronged main undercarriage design philosophy encompassing both four- and six-wheel bogies to stay within pavement loading limits.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350-900 has four-wheel bogies in a 4.1 m (13 ft) long bay.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The higher weight variant, the A350-1000 uses a six-wheel bogie, with a 4.7 m (15 ft) undercarriage bay.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] French-based Messier-Dowty provides the main undercarriage for the -900 variant, with titanium forgings from Kobelco, and UTC Aerospace Systems supplies the -1000 variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The nose gear is supplied by Liebherr Aerospace.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Honeywell supplies its 1,300-kilowatt (1,700-horsepower) HGT1700 auxiliary power unit with 10% greater power density than the TPE331 from which it is developed, and the air management system: the bleed air, environmental control, cabin pressure control and supplemental cooling systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus says that the new design provides a better cabin atmosphere with 20% humidity, a typical cabin altitude at or below 6,000 ft (1,800 m) and an airflow management system that adapts cabin airflow to passenger load with draught-free air circulation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The ram air turbine, with a nominal power of 50 kilovolt-amperes, is supplied by Hamilton Sundstrand and located in the lower surface of the fuselage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In light of the 787 Dreamliner battery problems, in February 2013 Airbus decided to revert from lithium-ion to the proven nickel-cadmium technology although the flight test programme will continue with the lithium-ion battery systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] 24 was delivered with 80 kg (176 lb) lighter Saft Li-ion batteries and in June 2017, fifty A350s were flying with them and benefiting from a two-year maintenance schedule instead of NiCd's 4–6 months.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Parker Hannifin supplies the complete fuel package: inerting system, fuel measurement and management systems, mechanical equipment and fuel pumps.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The fuel tank inerting system features air-separation modules to generate nitrogen-enriched air to reduce the flammability of fuel vapour in the tanks.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Parker also provides hydraulic power generation and distribution system: reservoirs, manifolds, accumulators, thermal control, isolation, software and new engine- and electric motor-driven pump designs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Parker estimates the contracts will generate more than US$2 billion in revenues over the life of the programme.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The revised design of the A350 XWB's glass cockpit dropped the A380-sized display and adopted 38 cm (15 in) liquid-crystal display screens.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus says the cockpit design allows for future advances in navigation technology to be placed on the displays plus gives flexibility and capacity to upload new software and to combine data from multiple sources and sensors for flight management and aircraft systems control.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] An optional head-up display is also present in the cockpit.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Avionics are a further development of the integrated modular avionics (IMA) concept found on the A380.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The A350's IMA will manage up to 40 functions (versus 23 functions for the A380) such as undercarriage, fuel, pneumatics, cabin environmental systems, and fire detection.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus stated that the benefits includes reduced maintenance and lower weight because as the IMA replaces multiple processors and LRUs with around 50% fewer standard computer modules known as line-replaceable modules.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The IMA runs on a 100 Mbit/s network based on the Avionics Full-Duplex Switched Ethernet standard, as employed in the A380, in place of the architecture used on the A330/A340.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2005, GE was the launch engine of the original A350, aiming for 2010 deliveries, while Rolls-Royce offered its Trent 1700.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] For the updated A350 XWB, GE offered a 87,000 lbf (390 kN) GEnx-3A87 for the A350-800/900, but not a higher thrust version needed for the A350-1000, which competes with the longer range 777 powered exclusively with the GE90-115B.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In December 2006, Rolls-Royce was selected for the A350 XWB launch engine.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The Rolls-Royce Trent XWB features a 300 cm (118 in) diameter fan and the design is based on the advanced developments of the Airbus A380 Trent 900 and the Boeing 787 Trent 1000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The higher-thrust version will have some modifications to the fan module—it will be the same diameter but will run slightly faster and have a new fan blade design—and run at increased temperatures allowed by new materials technologies from Rolls-Royce's research.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The Trent XWB may also benefit from the next-generation reduced acoustic mode scattering engine duct system (RAMSES), an acoustic quieting engine nacelle intake, and a carry-on design of the Airbus's "zero splice" intake liner developed for the A380.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] A "hot and high" rating option for Middle Eastern customers Qatar Airways, Emirates, and Etihad Airways keep its thrust available at higher temperatures and altitudes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus aimed to certify the A350 with 350-minute ETOPS capability on entry into service; although Airbus achieved a 370-minute ETOPS rating on 15 October 2014, which covers 99.7% of the Earth's surface.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] There are plans to extend this to 420 minutes in the future.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Engine thrust-reversers and nacelles are supplied by US-based Collins Aerospace (formerly UTC Aerospace Systems).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] One year after introduction, the A350 fleet had accumulated 3,000 flight cycles and around 16,000 block hours.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Finnair was operating the A350 at very high rates: 15 flight hours per day for Beijing, 18 hours for Shanghai, and more than 20 hours for Bangkok.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] This may have accelerated the retirement of the Airbus A340.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In service, problems occurred in three areas.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The onboard maintenance, repair, overhaul network needed software improvements.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus issued service bulletins regarding onboard equipment and removed galley inserts (coffee makers, toaster ovens) because of leaks.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus had to address spurious overheating warnings in the bleed air system by retrofitting an original connector with a gold-plated connector.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Airbus targeted a 98.5% dependability by the end of 2016 and to match the mature A330 in terms of reliability by early 2019.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] By the end of May 2016, the A350 fleet had flown 55,200 hours over 9,400 cycles at a 97.8% operational reliability on three months.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The longest operated sector was Qatar Airways' Adelaide–Doha at 13.8 hours for 6,120 nmi (11,334 km; 7,043 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The average flight was 6.8 hours, with the longest average being 9.6 hours by TAM Airlines and the shortest being 2.1 hours by Cathay Pacific's.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It is able to seat from 253 seats for Singapore Airlines to 348 seats for TAM Airlines, with a 30 to 46 seat business class and a 211 to 318 seat economy class, often including a premium economy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] A total of 49 A350s were delivered to customers in 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] It was also planned that the monthly rate would grow to 10 by the end of 2018, which was eventually achieved in 2019 when Airbus delivered 112 aircraft over a period of 11 months.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In January 2017, two years after introduction, 62 aircraft were in service with 10 airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] They had accumulated 25,000 flights over 154,000 hours with an average daily utilisation of 12.5 hours, and transported six million passengers with a 98.7% operational reliability.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Zodiac Aerospace encountered production difficulties with business class seats in their Texas and California factories.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] After a year, Cathay Pacific experienced cosmetic quality issues and upgraded or replaced the seats for the earliest cabins.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In 2017, average test flights before delivery decreased to 4.1 from 12 in 2014, with an average delay down to 25 days from 68.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In June 2017 after 30 months in commercial operation, 80 A350s were in service with 12 operators, the largest being Qatar Airways with 17 and 13 each at Cathay Pacific and Singapore Airlines (SIA).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The fleet average block time (time between pushback and destination gate arrival) was 7.2 hours with 53% below 3,000 nmi (5,556 km; 3,452 mi), 16% over 5,000 nmi (9,260 km; 5,754 mi), and 31% in between.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] LATAM Airlines had the longest average sector at 10.7 hours, and Asiana had the shortest at 3.8 hours.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Singapore Airlines operated the longest leg, Singapore to San Francisco 7,340 nmi (13,594 km; 8,447 mi), and the shortest leg, Singapore to Kuala Lumpur 160 nmi (296 km; 184 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Seating varied from 253 for Singapore Airlines to 389 for Air Caraïbes, with most between 280 and 320.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As of February 2018, 142 A350-900s had been delivered, and were in operation with a dispatch reliability of 99.3%.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As of November 2019, 33 operators had received 331 aircraft from 959 orders, and 2.6 million hours have been flown.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] As of October 2025, the global A350 fleet of 682 aircraft had completed more than 2,000,000 flights on more than 1,365 routes, and had carried more than 530 million passengers since its entry into service; the fleet had 99.2% operational reliability in the last 3 months.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In August 2021, as several A350s were sent in to be repainted in a scheme advertising the 2022 FIFA World Cup (played in Qatar), Qatar Airways discovered that their paint was unusually degraded.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The airline grounded its A350s until the root cause could be determined, and would not accept new aircraft deliveries until the problem could be solved.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The European civil aviation regulator, EASA, found that paint degradation did not affect the aircraft structure or introduce "other risks".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The Qatari civil aviation regulator was the only one that agreed with the airline that it was an airworthiness issue.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] In November 2021, Reuters found that Finnair, Cathay Pacific, Etihad, Lufthansa and Air France had also complained of paint damage as early as 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Singapore Airlines had not detected such problems with its fleet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] On 20 December 2021, Airbus received a formal legal claim in the English courts filed by Qatar Airways.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Qatar Airways alleged that the surface flaws cause the risk of fuel tank ignition due to the degradation in lightning protection over the fuel tanks in the wings.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Qatar Airways claimed it was owed US$200,000 per day in compensation for each grounded aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Meanwhile, according to a Flight International editorial, Airbus's decision to cancel Qatar's outstanding orders indicated that it was certain of its case.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] The court hearing was originally scheduled for summer 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] Both Airbus and Qatar Airways agreed to settle the dispute on 1 February 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p01] While the settlement was confidential, Flight International believed that Airbus achieved a more favourable outcome, opining that there was no major impact to Airbus's finances, the A350's reputation remained intact and Qatar's A321neos would nevertheless be delivered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The three main variants of the A350 were launched in 2006, with entry into service planned for 2013.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] At the 2011 Paris Air Show, Airbus postponed the entry into service of the A350-1000 by two years to mid-2017.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In July 2012, the A350's entry into service was delayed to the second half of 2014, before the -900 began service on 15 January 2015.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In October 2012, the -800 was due to enter service in mid-2016, but its development was cancelled in September 2014 in favour of the reengined Airbus A330neo.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350 is also offered as the ACJ350 corporate jet by Airbus Corporate Jets (ACJ), offering a 20,000 km; 12,400 mi (10,800 nmi) range for 25 passengers for the -900 derivative.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350-900 (ICAO code: A359) is the first A350 model; it has a MTOW of 283 tonnes (624,000 lb) when powered by the Trent XWB-84 or 255 tonnes (562,000 lb) when powered by the Trent XWB-75, typically seats 325 passengers, and has a range of 8,500 nmi (15,700 km; 9,800 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Airbus says that per seat, the Boeing 777-200ER should have a 16% heavier manufacturer's empty weight, a 30% higher block fuel consumption, and 25% higher cash operating costs than the A350-900.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The −900 is designed to compete with the Boeing 777-200LR and 787-10, while replacing the Airbus A340-500 and Boeing 777-200ER.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] A proposed A350−900R extended-range variant was to feature the higher engine thrust, strengthened structure, and landing gear of the 308 tonnes (679,000 lb) MTOW -1000 to give a further 800 nmi (1,500 km; 920 mi) range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Philippine Airlines (PAL) announced in 2016 that it will replace its A340-300 with an A350-900HGW ("high-gross weight") variant available from 2017 ,which it received in July 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] It enabled non-stop Manila-New York City flights without payload limitations in either direction, a 7,404 nmi (13,712 km; 8,520 mi) flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] This will enable an 8,100 nmi (15,000 km; 9,300 mi) range with 325 seats in a three-class layout.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In early November 2017, Emirates committed to purchase 40 Boeing 787-10 aircraft before Airbus presented an updated A350-900 layout with the rear pressure bulkhead pushed back by 2.5 ft (76 cm).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] After Emirates' Tim Clark was shown a ten-across economy cabin and galley changes, he said the -900 is "more marketable" as a result.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] By 2018, a 2014 build was valued $108M falling to $74.5M by 2022 while a new build was valued for $148M, a 6+12 year check cost $3M and an engine overhaul $4–6.5M.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The MTOW is increased by 5 tonnes (11,000 lb) from the previously certified 275 tonnes (606,000 lb) variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Because of the A350-900's fuel consumption of 5.8 tonnes (13,000 lb) per hour, it needs an additional 24 tonnes (53,000 lb) of fuel to fly 19 hours instead of the standard 15 hours: the increased MTOW and lower payloads will enable the larger fuel capacity.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Non-stop flights could last more than 20 hours.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The first −900ULR was rolled out without its engines in February 2018 for ground testing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Flight-tests after engine installation checked the larger fuel capacity and measured the performance improvements from the extended winglets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] It made its first flight on 23 April 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] There are no addition structural changes fitted to the A350-900ULR, therefore it retains the same type certificate and model name as the baseline A350-941.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The larger fuel capacity is enabled by integrating a modified fuel system to make use of the extra spaces in the centre wing box, no auxiliary fuel tanks are fitted.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Also the front cargo hold is disabled due to operational limits but can be reactivated depending on customer needs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Singapore Airlines, the launch customer, uses its seven -900ULR aircraft on non-stop flights between Singapore and New York City and cities on the U.S. west coast.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Singapore Airlines' seating is to range from 170 in largely business class seating up to over 250 in mixed seating.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The airline received its first -900ULR on 23 September 2018, with 67 business class seats and 94 premium economy seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] On 12 October 2018, it landed the world's then-longest flight at Newark Liberty International Airport from Singapore Changi after 17 hours and 52 minutes, covering 16,561 kilometres (8,942 nmi; 10,291 mi) for a 15,353 kilometres (8,290 nmi; 9,540 mi) orthodromic distance.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] It burned 101.4 t (224,000 lb) of fuel to cover the route in 17 h 22 min: an average of 5.8 tonnes per hour (1.6 kg/s).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] As of 2022, the A350-900ULR is used on the longest flight in the world, Singapore Airlines Flights 23 and 24 from Singapore to New York JFK.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] At the 2015 Dubai Air Show, John Leahy noted the demand of the Persian Gulf airlines for this variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In February 2018, Qatar Airways stated its preference for the larger -1000, having no need for the extra range of the -900ULR.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Compared to the standard -900, the -900ULR additional value is likely around $2 million.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Airbus Corporate Jet version of the A350, the ACJ350, is derived from the A350-900ULR.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] As a result of the increased fuel capacity from the -900ULR, the ACJ350 has a maximum range of 20,550 km (11,100 nmi; 12,770 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The German Air Force is to be the first to receive the ACJ350, having ordered three aircraft which will replace its two A340-300s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] After the Boeing 787-10 launch at the 2013 Paris Air Show, Airbus discussed with airlines a possible A350-900 Regional with a reduced MTOW of 250 t (550,000 lb).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Engine thrust would have been reduced to 70,000–75,000 lbf (310–330 kN) from the standard 85,000 lbf (380 kN) and the variant would have been optimised for routes up to 6,800 nmi (12,600 km; 7,800 mi) with seating for up to 360 passengers in a single-class layout.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350 Regional was expected to be ordered by Etihad Airways and Singapore Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Since 2013, there has been no further announcement about this variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Singapore Airlines selected an A350-900 version for medium-haul use, and Japan Airlines took delivery of a 369-seat A350-900 with a 217 t (478,000 lb) MTOW (WV018) for its domestic flight network.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350-1000 (ICAO code: A35K) is the largest variant of the A350 family at just under 74 metres (243 ft) in length.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] It seats 369 passengers in a typical two-class layout with a range of 9,000 nmi (17,000 km; 10,000 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] With a 9-across configuration, it is designed to replace the A340-600 and compete with the Boeing 777-300ER and 777-8.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Airbus estimates a 366-seat -1000 should have a 35 tonnes (77,000 lb) lighter operating empty weight than a 398-seat 777-9, a 15% lower trip cost, a 7% lower seat cost, and a 400 nmi (740 km; 460 mi) greater range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Compared to a Boeing 777-300ER with 360 seats, Airbus claims a 25% fuel burn per seat advantage for an A350-1000 with 369 seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The 7 m (23 ft) extension seats 40 more passengers with 40% more premium area.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The -1000 can match the 40 more seats of the 777-9 with a 10-across seating configuration but diminished comfort.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350-1000 has an 11-frame stretch over the −900 and a slightly larger wing than the −800/900 models with trailing-edge extension increasing its area by 4%.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] This will extend the high-lift devices and the ailerons, making the chord bigger by around 400 mm (16 in), optimising flap lift performance as well as cruise performance.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The main landing gear is a 6-wheel bogie instead of a 4-wheel bogie, put in a one frame longer bay.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The Rolls-Royce Trent XWB engine's thrust is augmented to 97,000 lbf (430 kN).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] These and other engineering upgrades are necessary so that the −1000 model maintains range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] It features an automatic emergency descent function to around 10,000 ft (3,000 m) and notifies air traffic control if the crew fails to respond to an alert, indicating possible incapacitation from depressurisation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The avionics software adaptation is activated by a push and pull button to avoid mistakes and could be retrofitted in the smaller -900.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] All performance targets have been met or exceeded, and it remains within its weight specification, unlike early −900s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Its 316 t MTOW appeared on 29 May 2018 update of its type certificate data sheet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] A further MTOW increase by 3 t (6,600 lb), to a total of 319 t (703,000 lb) was under study to be available from 2020 and could have been a response to Qantas' Project Sunrise.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In November 2019, maximum accommodation increased to 480 seats from 440 through the installation of new "Type-A+" exits, with a dual-lane evacuation slide.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] On 17 December 2021, French Bee took delivery of the first A350-1000 in this 480-seat configuration, leased by Air Lease Corporation and to be operated from Paris to Réunion, with 40 premium and 440 economy seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In October 2023, the variant's MTOW was raised again to 322 t (710,000 lb).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In December 2019, Qantas tentatively chose the A350-1000 to operate their Project Sunrise routes, before a final decision in March 2020 for up to 12 aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Initial speculation suggested that the variant might be marketed as the A350-1000ULR.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] However, the -1000 is not expected to share the -900ULR's larger fuel tanks and other fuel system modifications, and Airbus had stopped short of describing the largest MTOW variant as a ULR model, despite the 8,700 nmi (16,100 km; 10,000 mi) range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] After a delay due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the decision was confirmed on 2 May 2022, when Qantas placed a formal order for 12 Airbus A350-1000 aircraft for Project Sunrise flights to originally start in 2025.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] With Airbus integrating the tank into the A350-1000 for flight testing in early 2025 for delivery to the group in mid-2026.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] On 6 November 2025, Airbus and Qantas released a set of pictures of the upcoming first ultra long range A350-1000 variant (MSN 707) with a confirmed marketing name as A350-1000ULR being displayed on the aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] An A350-900 freighter was first mentioned in 2007, offering a similar capacity to the McDonnell Douglas MD-11F with a range of 9,250 km (5,000 nmi; 5,750 mi), to be developed after the passenger version.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In early 2020, Airbus was proposing an A350F before a potential launch.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The proposed freighter would be slightly longer than the A350-900 and Airbus would need 50 orders to launch the $2–3 billion programme.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In July 2021, the Airbus board approved the freighter development.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] As of 2021, it is based on the -1000 version for a payload over 90 tonnes, and entry into service targeted for 2025.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The A350F, also referred to by Airbus as the A350-1000F, would keep the 319-tonne MTOW previously announced for the passenger A350-1000 on a shortened fuselage, but the proposed design remains 6.9 m (23 ft) longer than the Boeing 777F with 10% larger freight volume at 695 m3 (24,500 cu ft).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] With a main deck cargo door behind the wing and reinforced main deck aluminium floor beams, its 111 t (245,000 lb) payload is higher than the 103.7 t (229,000 lb) of the 777F, while its empty weight is 30 tonnes (66,000 lb) lighter than the A350-1000, 20 tonnes (44,000 lb) lighter than the 777F.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The 70.8 m (232 ft) long cargo variant should have a 4,700 nmi (8,700 km; 5,400 mi) range at 109 tonnes structural payload.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] At the November 2021 Dubai Air Show, US lessor Air Lease Corporation became the launch customer with an order for seven to be delivered around 2026, among other Airbus airliners.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Air Lease Corporation cancelled its launch order in August 2025.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] The launch operator of the A350F was initially planned to be Singapore Airlines, which ordered seven aircraft at the 2022 Singapore Airshow with deliveries expected to begin in 2026.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In February 2025, Airbus announced that entry-into-service would be delayed until 2027 due to supply chain issues, particularly with Spirit Aerosystems which supplies the central fuselage section.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] After Air Lease Corporation's order cancellation, CMA CGM Air Cargo claimed in August 2025 that it would be the launch operator.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] In March 2026, Atlas Air announced a firm order for 20 A350Fs, marking the first time in its history that it would operate non-Boeing aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/airbus-a350-xwb-p02] Below is a list of major differences between the A350 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The **Boeing 747** is a long-range wide-body airliner designed and manufactured by Boeing Commercial Airplanes in the United States between 1968 and 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It was conceived in response to the demand of Pan Am for a jet 2+1⁄2 times the size of the 707, which had been introduced in October 1958, to reduce the airline's seat cost by 30%.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The design team was led by Joe Sutter, who left the 737 development program in 1965 to design the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In April 1966, Pan Am ordered 25 Boeing 747-100 aircraft, and in late 1966, Pratt & Whitney agreed to develop the JT9D engine, a high-bypass turbofan.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On September 30, 1968, the first 747 was rolled out of the purpose-built Everett Plant, the world's largest building by volume.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747's first flight took place on February 9, 1969, and the 747 was certified in December 1969.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It entered service with Pan Am on January 22, 1970.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 was the first airplane called a "Jumbo Jet" as the first wide-body airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 is a four-engined jet aircraft, initially powered by Pratt & Whitney JT9D turbofan engines, then General Electric CF6 and Rolls-Royce RB211 engines for the original variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] With a ten-abreast economy seating, it typically accommodates 366 passengers in three travel classes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It has a pronounced 37.5° wing sweep, allowing a Mach 0.85 (490 kn; 900 km/h) cruise speed, and its heavy weight is supported by four main landing gear legs, each with a four-wheel bogie.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The partial double-deck aircraft was designed with a raised cockpit so it could be converted to a freighter airplane by installing a front cargo door, as it was initially thought that it would eventually be superseded by supersonic transports.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing introduced the 747-200 in 1971, with uprated engines for a heavier maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) of 833,000 pounds (378 t) from the initial 735,000 pounds (333 t), increasing the maximum range from 4,620 to 6,560 nautical miles [nmi] (8,560 to 12,150 km; 5,320 to 7,550 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It was shortened for the longer-range 747SP in 1976, and the 747-300 followed in 1983 with a stretched upper deck for up to 400 seats in three classes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The heavier 747-400 with improved RB211 and CF6 engines or the new PW4000 engine (the JT9D successor), and a two-crew glass cockpit, was introduced in 1989 and is the most common variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After several studies, the stretched 747-8 was launched on November 14, 2005, using the General Electric GEnx engine first developed for the 787 Dreamliner (the inspiration for the -8 in the name), and was first delivered in October 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Initial competition came from the smaller trijet widebodies: the Lockheed L-1011 (introduced in 1972), McDonnell Douglas DC-10 (1971) and later MD-11 (1990).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Airbus competed with later variants with the heaviest versions of the A340 until surpassing the 747 in size with the A380, delivered between 2007 and 2021.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] These later variants of the 747 also faced internal competition from, and were ultimately superseded by, larger variants of the Boeing 777, such as the 777-300ER and 777-9.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Freighter variants of the 747 remain popular with cargo airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The final 747 was delivered to Atlas Air in January 2023 after a 54-year production run, with 1,574 aircraft built.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] As of October 2025, 65 Boeing 747s (4.1%) have been lost in accidents and incidents, in which a total of 3,746 people have died.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In 1963, the United States Air Force (USAF) began a series of study projects on an extremely large strategic transport aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Although the C-141 Starlifter was being introduced, officials believed that a much larger and more capable aircraft was needed, especially to carry cargo that would not fit in any existing aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The payload bay had to be 17 feet (5.18 m) wide by 13.5 feet (4.11 m) high and 100 feet (30 m) long with access through doors at the front and rear.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The desire to keep the number of engines to four required new engine designs with greatly increased power and better fuel economy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In May 1964, airframe proposals arrived from Boeing, Douglas, General Dynamics, Lockheed, and Martin Marietta; engine proposals were submitted by General Electric, Curtiss-Wright, and Pratt & Whitney.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing, Douglas, and Lockheed were given additional study contracts for the airframe, along with General Electric and Pratt & Whitney for the engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The airframe proposals shared several features.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] As the CX-HLS needed to be able to be loaded from the front, a door had to be included where the cockpit usually was.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In 1965, Lockheed's aircraft design and General Electric's engine design were selected for the new C-5 Galaxy transport, which was the largest military aircraft in the world at the time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing carried the nose door and raised cockpit concepts over to the design of the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 was conceived while air travel was increasing in the 1960s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The era of commercial jet transportation, led by the enormous popularity of the Boeing 707 and Douglas DC-8, had revolutionized long-distance travel.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Trippe also thought that airport congestion could be addressed by a larger aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In 1965, Joe Sutter was transferred from Boeing's 737 development team to manage the design studies for the new airliner, already assigned the model number 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Sutter began a study with Pan Am and other airlines to better understand their requirements.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] At the time, many thought that long-range subsonic airliners would eventually be superseded by supersonic transport aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing responded by designing the 747 so it could be easily adapted to carry freight and remain in production even if sales of the passenger version declined.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In April 1966, Pan Am ordered 25 Boeing 747-100 aircraft for US$525 million (equivalent to $3.9 billion in 2024 dollars).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] During the ceremonial 747 contract-signing banquet in Seattle on Boeing's 50th Anniversary, Juan Trippe predicted that the 747 would be "…a great weapon for peace, competing with intercontinental missiles for mankind's destiny".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] As launch customer, and because of its early involvement before placing a formal order, Pan Am was able to influence the design and development of the 747 to an extent unmatched by a single airline before or since.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Once additional orders for the aircraft were filed by Japan Airlines and Lufthansa, approval for production of the 747 was given in July 1966.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Ultimately, the high-winged CX-HLS Boeing design was not used for the 747, although technologies developed for their bid had an influence.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The original design included a full-length double-deck fuselage with eight-across seating and two aisles on the lower deck and seven-across seating and two aisles on the upper deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] However, concern over evacuation routes and limited cargo-carrying capability caused this idea to be scrapped in early 1966 in favor of a wider single deck design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The cockpit was therefore placed on a shortened upper deck so that a freight-loading door could be included in the nose cone; this feature produced the 747's distinctive "hump".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In early models, what to do with the small space in the pod behind the cockpit was not clear, and it was initially specified as a "lounge" area with no permanent seating.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] One of the principal technologies that enabled an aircraft as large as the 747 was the high-bypass turbofan engine.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] This engine technology was thought to be capable of delivering twice the power of the earlier turbojets while consuming one-third less fuel.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] General Electric had pioneered the concept but was committed to developing the engine for the C-5 Galaxy and did not enter the commercial market until later.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Pratt & Whitney was also working on the same principle and, by late 1966, Boeing, Pan Am and Pratt & Whitney agreed to develop a new engine, designated the JT9D to power the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The project was designed with a new methodology called fault tree analysis, which allowed the effects of a failure of a single part to be studied to determine its impact on other systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] To address concerns about safety and flyability, the 747's design included structural redundancy, redundant hydraulic systems, quadruple main landing gear and dual control surfaces.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Additionally, some of the most advanced high-lift devices used in the industry were included in the new design, to allow it to operate from existing airports.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] These included Krueger flaps running almost the entire length of the wing's leading edge, as well as complex three-part slotted flaps along the trailing edge of the wing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The wing's complex three-part flaps increased wing area by 21% and lift by 90% when fully deployed compared to their non-deployed configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing agreed to deliver the first 747 to Pan Am by the end of 1969.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] That date left 28 months to design the aircraft, just two-thirds of the normal time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The schedule was so fast-paced that the people who worked on it were given the nickname "The Incredibles".
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Developing the aircraft was such a technical and financial challenge that management was said to have "bet the company" when it started the project.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] For the 747SP, assembly was subcontracted to Japanese companies comprising Mitsubishi, Kawasaki, and Fuji, which were responsible for assembly of the inboard flaps, outboard flaps, and vertical rudder respectively.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing did not have a plant large enough to assemble the giant airliner, so they chose to build a new plant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The company considered locations in about 50 cities, and eventually decided to build the new plant some 30 miles (50 km) north of Seattle on a site adjoining a military base at Paine Field near Everett, Washington.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It bought the 780-acre (320 ha) site in June 1966.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Developing the 747 had been a major challenge, and building its assembly plant was also a huge undertaking.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Stamper, then head of the company's turbine division, to oversee construction of the Everett factory and to start production of the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] To level the site, more than four million cubic yards (three million cubic meters) of earth had to be moved.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Time was so short that the 747's full-scale mock-up was built before the factory roof above it was finished.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The plant is the largest building by volume ever built, and has been expanded several times to permit construction of other models of Boeing wide-body commercial jets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Before the first 747 was fully assembled, testing began on many components and systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] One important test involved the evacuation of 560 volunteers from a cabin mock-up via the aircraft's emergency chutes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The first full-scale evacuation took two and a half minutes instead of the maximum of 90 seconds mandated by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), and several volunteers were injured.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Subsequent test evacuations achieved the 90-second goal but caused more injuries.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Most problematic was evacuation from the aircraft's upper deck; instead of using a conventional slide, volunteer passengers escaped by using a harness attached to a reel.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Tests also involved taxiing such a large aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing built an unusual training device known as "Waddell's Wagon" (named for a 747 test pilot, Jack Waddell) that consisted of a mock-up cockpit mounted on the roof of a truck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] While the first 747s were still being built, the device allowed pilots to practice taxi maneuvers from a high upper-deck position.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In 1968, the program cost was US$1 billion (equivalent to $6.9 billion in 2024 dollars).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On September 30, 1968, the first 747 was rolled out of the Everett assembly building for the world's press and representatives of the 26 airlines that had ordered the airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Over the following months, preparations were made for the first flight, which took place on February 9, 1969, with test pilots Jack Waddell and Brien Wygle at the controls and Jess Wallick at the flight engineer's station.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Despite a minor problem with one of the flaps, the flight confirmed that the 747 handled extremely well.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 was found to be largely immune to "Dutch roll", a phenomenon that had been a major hazard to the early swept-wing jets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After the 747's introduction into commercial service in 1970, Boeing continued flight tests to address issues with the 747's design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] During later stages of the flight test program, flutter testing showed that the wings suffered oscillation under certain conditions.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] This difficulty was partly solved by reducing the stiffness of some wing components.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] However, a particularly severe high-speed flutter problem was solved only by inserting depleted uranium counterweights as ballast in the outboard engine nacelles of the early 747s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The flight test program was hampered by problems with the 747's JT9D engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Difficulties included engine stalls caused by rapid throttle movements and distortion of the turbine casings after a short period of service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The problems delayed 747 deliveries for several months; up to 20 aircraft at the Everett plant were stranded while awaiting engine installation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The program was further delayed when one of the five test aircraft suffered serious damage during a landing attempt at Renton Municipal Airport, the site of Boeing's Renton factory.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The incident happened on December 13, 1969, when a test aircraft was flown to Renton to have test equipment removed and a cabin installed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Cokely undershot the airport's short runway and the 747's right, outer landing gear was torn off and two engine nacelles were damaged.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] However, these difficulties did not prevent Boeing from taking a test aircraft to the 28th Paris Air Show in mid-1969, where it was displayed to the public for the first time.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Finally, in December 1969, the 747 received its FAA airworthiness certificate, clearing it for introduction into service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Pan Am introduced the first 747 service the following year on January 22, 1970.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The huge cost of developing the 747 and building the Everett factory meant that Boeing had to borrow heavily from a banking syndicate.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] During the final months before delivery of the first aircraft, the company had to repeatedly request additional funding to complete the project.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Had this been refused, Boeing's survival would have been threatened.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The firm's debt exceeded $2 billion, with $1.2 billion owed to the banks setting a record for all companies.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Allen later said, "It was really too large a project for us." Ultimately, the gamble succeeded, and Boeing held a monopoly in very large passenger aircraft production for many years.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After the initial 747-100, Boeing developed the -100B, a higher maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) variant, and the -100SR (Short Range), with higher passenger capacity.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Increased maximum takeoff weight allows aircraft to carry more fuel and have longer range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The -200 model followed in 1971, featuring more powerful engines and a higher MTOW.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Passenger, freighter and combination passenger-freighter versions of the -200 were produced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The shortened 747SP (special performance) with a longer range was also developed, and entered service in 1976.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing primarily focused on improving payload capabilities during the development and testing of the 747-200 and its subvariants in the 1970s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Weight trials were conducted between October and November of 1970 at Edwards Air Force Base with the prototype 747-200B, which reached a maximum takeoff weight of 820,700 pounds (372.3 t) during a test flight on November 12.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] At that time, the aircraft held the record for the heaviest takeoff weight until heavier and more powerful 747-200 airframes were built.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On November 1, 1976, the first RB211-powered 747-200 set a world record for maximum mass lifted during a trial flight at NAS Lemoore, where it flew up to 6,562 feet (2,000 meters) with a weight of 840,500 pounds (381.2 t).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 line was further developed with the launch of the 747-300 on June 11, 1980, followed by interest from Swissair a month later and the go-ahead for the project.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 300 series resulted from Boeing studies to increase the seating capacity of the 747, during which modifications such as fuselage plugs and extending the upper deck over the entire length of the fuselage were rejected.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The first 747-300, completed in 1983, included a stretched upper deck, increased cruise speed, and increased seating capacity.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The -300 variant was previously designated 747SUD for stretched upper deck, then 747-200 SUD, followed by 747EUD, before the 747-300 designation was used.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Passenger, short range and combination freighter-passenger versions of the 300 series were produced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After the publication of Abraham's *Aviation Week & Space Technology* interview, more airlines became vocal about expressing their demands for a modernized 747, to which Boeing responded by launching the development of the longer-range 747-400 in October 1985.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Development costs soared, and production delays occurred as new technologies were incorporated at the request of airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Insufficient workforce experience and reliance on overtime contributed to early production problems on the 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 remained the heaviest commercial aircraft in regular service until the debut of the Antonov An-124 Ruslan in 1982; variants of the 747-400 surpassed the An-124's weight in 2000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo transport, which debuted in 1988, remains the world's largest aircraft by several measures (including the most accepted measures of maximum takeoff weight and length); one aircraft has been completed and was in service until 2022 when it was destroyed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The Scaled Composites Stratolaunch is currently the largest aircraft by wingspan.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After the arrival of the 747-400, several stretching schemes for the 747 were proposed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing announced the larger 747-500X and -600X preliminary designs in 1996.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The new variants would have cost more than US$5 billion, and interest was not sufficient to continue.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In 2000, Boeing offered the more modest 747X and 747X stretch derivatives as alternatives to the Airbus A38X.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] However, the 747X family was unable to attract enough interest to enter production.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] A year later, Boeing switched from the 747X studies to pursue the Sonic Cruiser, and after the Sonic Cruiser program was put on hold, the 787 Dreamliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Some of the ideas developed for the 747X were used on the 747-400ER, a longer range variant of the 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After several variants were proposed but abandoned, some industry observers became skeptical of new aircraft proposals from Boeing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] However, in early 2004, Boeing announced plans for the 747 Advanced that were eventually adopted.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Similar in nature to the 747-X, the stretched 747 Advanced used technology from the 787 to modernize the design and its systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 remained the largest passenger airliner in service until the Airbus A380 began airline service in 2007.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On November 14, 2005, Boeing announced it was launching the 747 Advanced as the Boeing 747-8.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] As of 2011, most orders of the 747-8 were for the freighter variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On February 8, 2010, the 747-8 Freighter made its maiden flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The first delivery of the 747-8 went to Cargolux in 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The first 747-8 Intercontinental passenger variant was delivered to Lufthansa on May 5, 2012.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 1,500th Boeing 747 was delivered in June 2014 to Lufthansa.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In January 2016, Boeing stated it was reducing 747-8 production to six per year beginning in September 2016, incurring a $569 million post-tax charge against its fourth-quarter 2015 profits.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] At the end of 2015, the company had 20 orders outstanding.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On January 29, 2016, Boeing announced that it had begun the preliminary work on the modifications to a commercial 747-8 for the next Air Force One presidential aircraft, then expected to be operational by 2020.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On July 12, 2016, Boeing announced that it had finalized an order from Volga-Dnepr Group for 20 747-8 freighters, valued at $7.58 billion (~$9.68 billion in 2024) at list prices.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Four aircraft were delivered beginning in 2012.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Volga-Dnepr Group is the parent of three major Russian air-freight carriers – Volga-Dnepr Airlines, AirBridgeCargo Airlines and Atran Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The new 747-8 freighters would replace AirBridgeCargo's current 747-400 aircraft and expand the airline's fleet and will be acquired through a mix of direct purchases and leasing over the next six years, Boeing said.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On July 27, 2016, in its quarterly report to the Securities and Exchange Commission, Boeing discussed the termination of 747 production due to insufficient demand.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] With a firm order backlog of 21 aircraft and a production rate of six per year, program accounting had been reduced to 1,555 aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] In October 2016, UPS Airlines ordered 14 -8Fs to add capacity, with options for 14, added in February 2018 to increase the total to 28 -8Fs on order.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The backlog then stood at 25 aircraft, though several of these were orders from airlines that no longer intended to take delivery.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On July 2, 2020, it was reported that Boeing planned to end 747 production in 2022 upon delivery of the remaining jets for UPS and the Volga-Dnepr Group, due to low demand.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On July 29, 2020, Boeing confirmed that the final 747 would be delivered in 2022 as a result of "current market dynamics and outlook" stemming from the COVID-19 pandemic, according to CEO David Calhoun.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The last aircraft, a 747-8F for Atlas Air registered N863GT, rolled off the production line on December 6, 2022, and was delivered on January 31, 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing hosted an event at the Everett factory for thousands of workers as well as industry executives to commemorate the delivery.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 is a large, wide-body (two-aisle) airliner with four wing-mounted engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Its wings have a high sweep angle of 37.5° for a fast, efficient cruise speed of Mach 0.84 to 0.88, depending on the variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The sweep also reduces the wingspan, allowing the 747 to use existing hangars.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Its seating capacity is over 366 with a 3–4–3 seat arrangement (two aisles with three seats on each side and four seats in the middle) in economy class and a 2–3–2 layout in first class on the main deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The upper deck has a 3–3 seat arrangement in economy class and a 2–2 layout in first class.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Lavatories for later passenger models built from the 1980s onwards could be placed anywhere in the cabin through the installation of a central waste disposal system, dubbed the "sewer system", powered by an electric pump to provide suction.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The "sewer system" was proposed by KLM chief engineer Gerald Lamb and initially tested on the Boeing 767 before its installation on 747s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Seated 2 ft 7 in (0.79 m) above the floor of the main deck, the cockpit creates a hump.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] This raised cockpit allows front loading of cargo on freight variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The upper deck behind the cockpit provides space for a lounge and/or extra seating.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Some operators also configured the upper deck with features other than passenger seating or lounges, such as the *Skybeds* of Philippine Airlines' 747-200Bs, which provided passengers with genuine beds fitted with seatbelts, enabling them to sleep during long-haul sectors.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The "stretched upper deck" became available as an alternative on the 747-100B variant and later as a standard configuration beginning with the 747-300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The upper deck was stretched further on the 747-8.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 cockpit roof section also has an escape hatch, from which the cockpit crew can exit during an emergency if they cannot do so through the cabin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] An inertial reel attached to a cable is provided for each crew member to hold onto while exiting through the hatch and sliding down to the ground.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The main gear is redundant so that landing can be performed on two opposing landing gears if the others are not functioning properly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The bogies on the main fuselage are positioned behind the wing to accommodate heavy payloads and balance the load away from the nose gear, especially during takeoff and landing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The ground steering system of the landing gear enables the main gear bogies to move in concert with the nose gear.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] All tires on the landing gear are tubeless and identical in size to facilitate interchangeability.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] To minimize the overheating issues with steel brakes, the 747-400 was designed with carbon brakes for faster cooling.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The -400 also provided instrumentation that enabled the cockpit panel to display tire pressure values.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 has split control surfaces and was designed with sophisticated triple-slotted flaps that minimize landing speeds and allow the 747 to use standard-length runways.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] To transport spare engines, the 747 can accommodate a non-functioning fifth-pod engine under the aircraft's port wing between the inner functioning engine and the fuselage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Use of the fifth engine pod increases drag on the left side of the aircraft, which pilots need to compensate for to maintain a consistent heading, sometimes by offsetting the rudder to the right side at cruise.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It was eventually ruled out as a cause of the crash after evaluation of the aircraft's flight data recorder (FDR) found no anomalies in the aircraft's handling, and the incident was revealed to have been caused by a terrorist bombing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The fifth engine mount point was used by Virgin Orbit's LauncherOne program to carry an orbital-class rocket to cruise altitude where it was deployed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 Classic variants, comprising the -100/200/300/SP, were designed to be flown by two pilots and a flight engineer relying on then-innovative electro-mechanical analog instruments for flight operations, which are either dual or triple redundant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Specifications of individual aircraft were delivered in accordance with the requests of their respective customers, who were given the option to customize cockpit layouts through means such as choosing to install either dial or tape-style gauges.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The introduction of digital cockpit displays on the 747-400 later gave pilots the option to choose between displaying either dial or tape-style indicators by programming the display driver without the need to reinstrument the cockpit as was done for the Classic variants' analog cockpits.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Unlike the earlier 707, the 747 did not need a navigator in the cockpit, as it was the first commercial aircraft to utilize an inertial navigation system (INS).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Among the other advanced technologies included in the 747 were an autothrottle for automatic airspeed control and a performance management system (PMS).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747-400, launched in October 1985, replaced analog instruments with electronic flight instrument systems (EFIS) similar to those of the Boeing 757 and 767.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] These technologies reduced the number of cockpit instruments to 300 indicators and 200 switches from the nearly 690 dials and lights and 280 switches found in Classic variants, and they also enabled the -400 to be manned by two pilots, eliminating the flight engineer's position of previous variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On average, a 747 Classic airframe has approximately 135 miles (215 km) of electrical wiring and 1 mile (1.6 km) of hydraulics to power its systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The wiring was reduced by about 30% for the 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] On January 15, 1970, First Lady Pat Nixon christened Pan Am's first 747 at Dulles International Airport in the presence of Pan Am chairman Najeeb Halaby.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Instead of champagne, red, white, and blue water was sprayed on the aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 then subsequently entered service on January 22, 1970, on Pan Am's New York–London route.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The flight had been planned for the evening of January 21 but was delayed due to engine overheating on the original aircraft (Clipper Young America, registration N735PA).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Finding a substitute delayed the flight by more than six hours to the following day when Clipper Victor (registration N736PA) was used.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 enjoyed a fairly smooth introduction into service, overcoming concerns that some airports would not be able to accommodate an aircraft that large.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Although technical problems occurred, they were relatively minor and quickly solved.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] After the aircraft's introduction with launch customer Pan Am in 1970, many other airlines that had bought the 747 to stay competitive began to put their own 747s into service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Within months after the inaugural 747 service, Pan Am faced competition on international routes from other US-based carriers, such as Trans World Airlines (TWA) and Northwest Airlines, as well as foreign carriers like Air France, Lufthansa, and Japan Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Lufthansa would inaugurate the first 747 freighter service with the introduction of the 747-200F in 1972 and remained the sole freighter operator until more airlines placed orders for 747 freighters in 1974.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Boeing estimated that half of the early 747 sales were to airlines desiring the aircraft's long range rather than its payload capacity.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] While the 747 had the lowest potential operating cost per seat, this could only be achieved when the aircraft was fully loaded; costs per seat increased rapidly as occupancy declined.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] A moderately loaded 747, one with only 70 percent of its seats occupied, used more than 95 percent of the fuel needed by a fully occupied 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Nonetheless, many flag-carriers purchased the 747 due to its prestige, "even if it made no sense economically" to operate.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] During its production run, the 747 primarily faced competition from the McDonnell Douglas DC-10 and Lockheed L-1011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Many international carriers used the 747 on Pacific routes, while ANA and Japan Airlines deployed short-range 747 models on Japanese domestic routes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] International flights bypassing traditional hub airports and landing at smaller cities became more common throughout the 1980s, thus eroding the 747's original market.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] By 1982, a total of 542 747s were in active service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] It was most prominent in the Asia-Pacific region, where 169 examples, 31% of the global fleet, were in service with airlines based in the region.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] Indeed, tri- and quadjet designs from the same era - including the Airbus A380, which was designed to compete directly with the 747 - struggled to reach commercial success.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The 747 has seen military service worldwide either in dedicated fleets or through charter operations.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p01] The Israeli Air Force (IAF) notably set a record with the 747 in 1991, when 1,087 passengers were flown in an El Al 747-200C during Operation Solomon, a covert operation to airlift Ethiopian Jews from Addis Ababa to Tel Aviv.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-100 with a range of 4,620 nautical miles (8,556 km), was the original variant launched in 1966.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200 soon followed, with its launch in 1968 and the shorter 747SP launched in 1973.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Ultimately, the 747-8 was announced in 2005.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Several versions of each variant have been produced, and many of the early variants were in production simultaneously.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) classifies variants using a shortened code formed by combining the model number and the variant designator (e.g.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first 747-100s were built with six upper deck windows (three per side) to accommodate upstairs lounge areas.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Later, as airlines began to use the upper deck for premium passenger seating instead of lounge space, Boeing offered an upper deck with ten windows on either side as an option, which was first applied on airframes built for United Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Some early -100s were retrofitted with the new configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -100 was equipped with Pratt & Whitney JT9D engines and was compatible with the JT9D-1, -3, -3A, -3W, -7, and -7W variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 168 747-100s were built; 167 were delivered to customers, while Boeing kept the prototype, *City of Everett*.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 1972, its unit cost was US$24 million (184.7 million today).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Responding to requests from Japanese airlines for a high-capacity aircraft to serve domestic routes between major cities, Boeing developed the 747SR as a short-range version of the 747-100 with lower fuel capacity and greater payload capability.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] With increased economy class seating, up to 498 passengers could be carried in early versions and up to 550 in later models.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Intended for shorter routes and thus more turn arounds, the 747SR had an economic design life objective of 52,000 flights during 20 years of operation, compared to 24,600 flights in 20 years for the standard 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The initial 747SR model, the -100SR, had a strengthened body structure and landing gear to accommodate the added stress accumulated from a greater number of takeoffs and landings.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Extra structural support was built into the wings, fuselage, and the landing gear along with a 20% reduction in fuel capacity.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The initial order for the -100SR – four aircraft for Japan Air Lines (JAL, later Japan Airlines) – was announced on October 30, 1972; rollout occurred on August 3, 1973, and the first flight took place on August 31, 1973.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The type was certified by the FAA on September 26, 1973, with the first delivery on the same day.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -100SR entered service with JAL, the type's sole customer, on October 7, 1973, and typically operated flights within Japan.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Seven -100SRs were built between 1973 and 1975, each with a 520,000-pound (240 t) MTOW and Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7A engines derated to 43,000 pounds-force (190 kN) of thrust.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Following the -100SR, Boeing produced the -100BSR, a 747SR variant with increased takeoff weight capability.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Debuting in 1978, the -100BSR also incorporated structural modifications for a high cycle-to-flying hour ratio; a related standard -100B model debuted in 1979.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -100BSR first flew on November 3, 1978, with first delivery to All Nippon Airways (ANA) on December 21, 1978.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 20 -100BSRs were produced for ANA and JAL.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -100BSR had a 600,000 pounds (270 t) MTOW and was powered by the same JT9D-7A or General Electric CF6-45 engines used on the -100SR.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] ANA operated this variant on domestic Japanese routes with 455 or 456 seats until retiring its last aircraft in March 2006.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 1986, two -100BSR SUD models, featuring the stretched upper deck (SUD) of the -300, were produced for JAL.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The type's maiden flight occurred on February 26, 1986, with FAA certification and first delivery on March 24, 1986.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] JAL operated the -100BSR SUD with 563 seats on domestic routes until their retirement in the third quarter of 2006.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] While only two -100BSR SUDs were produced, in theory, standard -100Bs can be modified to the SUD certification.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-100B model was developed from the -100SR, using its stronger airframe and landing gear design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The type had an increased fuel capacity of 48,070 US gal (182,000 L), allowing for a 5,000-nautical-mile (9,300 km; 5,800 mi) range with a typical 452-passenger payload, and an increased MTOW of 750,000 lb (340 t) was offered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first -100B order, one aircraft for Iran Air, was announced on June 1, 1978.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] This version first flew on June 20, 1979, received FAA certification on August 1, 1979, and was delivered the next day.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Nine -100Bs were built, one for Iran Air and eight for Saudi Arabian Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Unlike the original -100, the -100B was offered with Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7A, CF6-50, or Rolls-Royce RB211-524 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] However, only RB211-524 (Saudia) and JT9D-7A (Iran Air) engines were ordered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The last 747-100B, EP-IAM was retired by Iran Air in 2014, the last commercial operator of the 747-100 and -100B.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The development of the 747SP stemmed from a joint request between Pan American World Airways and Iran Air, who were looking for a high-capacity airliner with enough range to cover Pan Am's New York–Middle Eastern routes and Iran Air's planned Tehran–New York route.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The Tehran–New York route, when launched, was the longest non-stop commercial flight in the world.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Fuselage sections were eliminated fore and aft of the wing, and the center section of the fuselage was redesigned to fit mating fuselage sections.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The SP's flaps used a simplified single-slotted configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747SP, compared to earlier variants, had a tapering of the aft upper fuselage into the empennage, a double-hinged rudder, and longer vertical and horizontal stabilizers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Power was provided by Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7(A/F/J/FW) or Rolls-Royce RB211-524 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747SP was granted a type certificate on February 4, 1976, and entered service with launch customers Pan Am and Iran Air that same year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The aircraft was chosen by airlines wishing to serve major airports with short runways.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 45 747SPs were built, with the 44th 747SP delivered on August 30, 1982.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 1987, Boeing re-opened the 747SP production line after five years to build one last 747SP for an order by the United Arab Emirates government.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In addition to airline use, one 747SP was modified for the NASA/German Aerospace Center SOFIA experiment.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Iran Air, the last civil operator of the type, retired its final 747-SP (EP-IAC) in June 2016.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] pictured in 1972, had three windows per side on the upper deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The same aircraft, pictured in 1988, retrofitted with the ten-window upper deck configuration that was standardized later in production.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing offered retrofits to apply the ten-window configuration on the upper decks of 747-100s and -200s with the older three-window layout.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] While the 747-100 powered by Pratt & Whitney JT9D-3A engines offered enough payload and range for medium-haul operations, it was marginal for long-haul route sectors.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The demand for longer-range aircraft with increased payload quickly led to the improved -200, which featured more powerful engines, increased MTOW, and greater range than the -100.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200 was produced in passenger (-200B), freighter (-200F), convertible (-200C), and combi (-200M) versions and was partly influenced by design inputs from the KSSU airline consortium comprising KLM, Scandinavian Airlines, Swissair, and Union de Transports Aériens (UTA).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Externally, the appearance of the 747-200 is identical to that of the earlier 747-100.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A few -200s retained the early three-window configuration on the upper deck, but most were built with a ten-window configuration on each side starting with the 147th aircraft built, a 747-200B delivered to Qantas.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Retrofits were also offered to apply the ten-window upper deck configuration on early 747s with the three-window configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200B was the basic passenger version, with increased fuel capacity and more powerful engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In its first three years of production, the -200 was equipped with Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7 engines, initially the only engine available.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -200 was later made compatible with the JT9D-7J, -7Q, -7AW, -70A, and -7R4G2 variants throughout its production run.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Range with a full passenger load started at over 5,000 nmi (9,300 km; 5,800 mi) and increased to 6,000 nmi (11,000 km; 6,900 mi) with later engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Extra fuel tanks were installed on two of the 747-200Bs delivered to Japan Airlines in the 1980s to increase the fuel capacity from 158.8 to 164.1 short tons (144.1 to 148.9 t), enabling them to be used on the airline's nonstop flights between Tokyo and New York.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Most -200Bs had an internally stretched upper deck, allowing for up to 16 passenger seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The freighter model, the 747-200F, had a hinged nose cargo door and could be fitted with an optional side cargo door, and had a capacity of 105 short tons (95 t) and an MTOW of up to 833,000 pounds (378 t).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200F was first flown on October 14, 1971, and entered service with Lufthansa in March 1972.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The convertible version, the 747-200C, could be converted between a passenger and a freighter or used in mixed configurations, and featured removable seats and a nose cargo door.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -200C could also be outfitted with an optional side cargo door on the main deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first -200C rolled out of Boeing's Everett factory on February 28, 1973, and made its maiden flight a month later before its delivery to launch customer World Airways on April 27.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200C's unique feature proved to be beneficial for its operators in maintaining profitable 747 operations through switching between configurations depending on the flow of passenger and freight traffic on their networks.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] For instance, Martinair flew its 747-200Cs in the 1980s and 1990s as passenger aircraft in the summer and as freighters in the winter.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The combi aircraft model, the 747-200M (originally designated 747-200BC), was based on a configuration first applied in 1974 as a conversion for Sabena's 747-100 fleet and could carry freight in the rear section of the main deck via a side cargo door.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A removable partition on the main deck separated the cargo area at the rear from the passengers at the front.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -200M could carry up to 238 passengers in a three-class configuration with cargo carried on the main deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The model was also known as the 747-200 Combi.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first -200M made its maiden flight on November 18, 1974, and was delivered to Air Canada on March 7, 1975.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As on the -100, a stretched upper deck (SUD) modification was later offered in the 1980s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Between September 1984 and March 1986, all ten of the CF6-powered 747-200s in KLM's fleet were converted with a process that involved removing half of the upper fuselage up to the leading edge of the wing, where the new SUD section would be installed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Two -200 airframes operated by UTA were also modified with the SUD conversion.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -200 was the first 747 to provide a choice of powerplant from the three major engine manufacturers, namely Pratt & Whitney, General Electric, and Rolls-Royce.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] After launching the -200 with Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7 engines on August 1, 1972, Boeing announced that it had reached an agreement with General Electric to certify the 747 with CF6-50 series engines to increase the aircraft's market potential.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The CF6-50 was initially tested on the prototype 747 before the first civilian CF6-powered airframe, a 747-200M, was delivered to KLM in October 1975.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-200 was compatible with the CF6-50D and CF6-50E variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Rolls-Royce followed 747 engine production with the announcement of the RB211-524B engine as an option for the 747 on June 17, 1975, and a launch order from British Airways for four aircraft, the first of which was delivered to the airline on June 16, 1977.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first RB211-powered 747-200 made its maiden flight on September 3, 1976, and received FAA certification in May 1977.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Specific variants of the RB211 that were compatible with the 747-200 included the RB211-524B2 and -524C2.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 393 of the 747-200 versions had been built when production ended in 1991.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Iran Air retired the last passenger 747-200 in May 2016, 36 years after it was delivered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As of July 2019, five 747-200s remain in service as freighters.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The stretched upper deck (SUD) has two emergency exit doors and is the most visible difference between the -300 and previous models.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] After being made standard on the 747-300, the SUD was offered as a retrofit, and as an option to earlier variants still in-production.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] An example for a retrofit were two UTA -200 Combis being converted in 1986, and an example for the option were two brand-new JAL -100 aircraft (designated -100BSR SUD), the first of which was delivered on March 24, 1986.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-300 introduced a new straight stairway to the upper deck, instead of a spiral staircase on earlier variants, which creates room above and below for more seats.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Minor aerodynamic changes allowed the -300's cruise speed to reach Mach 0.85 compared with Mach 0.84 on the -200 and -100 models, while retaining the same takeoff weight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -300 could be equipped with the same Pratt & Whitney and Rolls-Royce powerplants as on the -200, as well as updated General Electric CF6-80C2B1 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Swissair placed the first order for the 747-300 on June 11, 1980.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The variant revived the 747-300 designation, which had been previously used on a trijet design study that did not reach production.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-300 first flew on October 5, 1982, and the type's first delivery went to Swissair on March 23, 1983.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Besides the passenger model, two other versions (-300M, -300SR) were produced.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-300M features cargo capacity on the rear portion of the main deck, similar to the -200M, but with the stretched upper deck it can carry more passengers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-300SR, a short range, high-capacity domestic model, was produced for Japanese markets with a maximum seating for 584.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] No production freighter version of the 747-300 was built, but Boeing began modifications of used passenger -300 models into freighters in 2000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 81 747-300 series aircraft were delivered, 56 for passenger use, 21 -300M and 4 -300SR versions.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 1985, just two years after the -300 entered service, the type was superseded by the announcement of the more advanced 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The last 747-300 was delivered in September 1990 to Sabena.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] While some -300 customers continued operating the type, several large carriers replaced their 747-300s with 747-400s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Air France, Air India, Japan Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Qantas were some of the last major carriers to operate the 747-300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] On December 29, 2008, Qantas flew its last scheduled 747-300 service, operating from Melbourne to Los Angeles via Auckland.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In July 2015, Pakistan International Airlines retired their final 747-300 after 30 years of service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Mahan Air was the last passenger operator of the 747-300.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 2022, one of their 747-300Ms was leased by Emtrasur Cargo.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-300M was later seized by the US Department of Justice in 2024.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400 is an improved model with increased range.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] It has wingtip extensions of 6 ft (1.8 m) and winglets of 6 ft (1.8 m), which improve the type's fuel efficiency by four percent compared to previous 747 versions.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400 introduced a new glass cockpit designed for a flight crew of two instead of three, with a reduction in the number of dials, gauges and knobs from 971 to 365 through the use of electronics.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The type also features tail fuel tanks, revised engines, and a new interior.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The longer range has been used by some airlines to bypass traditional fuel stops, such as Anchorage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Powerplants include the Pratt & Whitney PW4062, General Electric CF6-80C2, and Rolls-Royce RB211-524.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As a result of the Boeing 767 development overlapping with the 747-400's development, both aircraft can use the same three powerplants and are even interchangeable between the two aircraft models.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -400 was offered in passenger (-400), freighter (-400F), combi (-400M), domestic (-400D), extended range passenger (-400ER), and extended range freighter (-400ERF) versions.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Passenger versions retain the same upper deck as the -300, while the freighter version does not have an extended upper deck.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400D was designed for short-range operations with maximum seating for 624.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] So winglets were not included though they can be retrofitted.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Cruising speed is up to Mach 0.855 on different versions of the 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The passenger version first entered service in February 1989 with launch customer Northwest Airlines on the Minneapolis to Phoenix route.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The combi version entered service in September 1989 with KLM, while the freighter version entered service in November 1993 with Cargolux.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400ERF entered service with Air France in October 2002, while the 747-400ER entered service with Qantas, its sole customer, in November 2002.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In January 2004, Boeing and Cathay Pacific launched the 747-400 Special Freighter program, later referred to as the Boeing Converted Freighter (BCF), to modify passenger 747-400s for cargo use.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first 747-400BCF was redelivered in December 2005.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In March 2007, Boeing announced that it had no plans to produce further passenger versions of the -400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] However, orders for 36 -400F and -400ERF freighters were already in place at the time of the announcement.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The last passenger version of the 747-400 was delivered in April 2005 to China Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Some of the last built 747-400s were delivered with Dreamliner livery along with the modern Signature interior from the Boeing 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A total of 694 of the 747-400 series aircraft were delivered.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] At various times, the largest 747-400 operator has included Singapore Airlines, Japan Airlines, and British Airways.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As of July 2019, 331 Boeing 747-400s were in service; there were only 10 Boeing 747-400s in passenger service as of September 2021.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400 Dreamlifter (originally called the 747 Large Cargo Freighter or LCF) is a Boeing-designed modification of existing 747-400s into a larger outsize cargo freighter configuration to ferry 787 Dreamliner sub-assemblies.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Evergreen Aviation Technologies Corporation of Taiwan was contracted to complete modifications of 747-400s into Dreamlifters in Taoyuan.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The aircraft flew for the first time on September 9, 2006, in a test flight.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Modification of four aircraft was completed by February 2010.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The Dreamlifters have been placed into service transporting sub-assemblies for the 787 program to the Boeing plant in Everett, Washington, for final assembly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The aircraft is certified to carry only essential crew with no passengers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing announced a new 747 variant, the 747-8, on November 14, 2005.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Referred to as the *747 Advanced* prior to its launch, Boeing selected the designation 747-8 to show the connection with the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, as the aircraft would use technology and the General Electric GEnx engines from the 787 to modernize the design and its systems.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The variant is designed to be quieter, more economical, and more environmentally friendly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-8's fuselage is lengthened from 232 feet (71 m) to 251 feet (77 m), marking the first stretch variant of the aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-8 Freighter, or 747-8F, has 16% more payload capacity than its predecessor, allowing it to carry seven more standard air cargo containers, with a maximum payload capacity of 154 short tons (140 t) of cargo.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As on previous 747 freighters, the 747-8F features a flip up nose-door, a side-door on the main deck, and a side-door on the lower deck ("belly") to aid loading and unloading.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-8F made its maiden flight on February 8, 2010.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The variant received its amended type certificate jointly from the FAA and the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) on August 19, 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The -8F was first delivered to Cargolux on October 12, 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The passenger version, named 747-8 Intercontinental or 747-8I, is designed to carry up to 467 passengers in a 3-class configuration and fly more than 8,000 nautical miles (15,000 km; 9,200 mi) at Mach 0.855.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As a derivative of the already common 747-400, the 747-8I has the economic benefit of similar training and interchangeable parts.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The type's first test flight occurred on March 20, 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-8 has surpassed the Airbus A340-600 as the world's longest airliner, a record it would hold until the 777X, which first flew in 2020.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The first -8I was delivered in May 2012 to Lufthansa.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-8 received 155 total orders, including 106 for the -8F and 47 for the -8I as of June 2021.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The final 747-8F was delivered to Atlas Air on January 31, 2023, marking the end of the production of the Boeing 747 series.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The final aircraft was registered as N863GT.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Below is a list of major differences between the original 747 variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing studied a number of 747 variants that did not advance beyond the concept stage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] During the late 1960s and early 1970s, Boeing studied the development of a shorter 747 with three engines, to compete with the smaller Lockheed L-1011 TriStar and McDonnell Douglas DC-10.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The center engine would have been fitted in the tail with an S-duct intake similar to the L-1011's.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Overall, the 747 trijet would have had more payload, range, and passenger capacity than either of the two other aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] However, engineering studies showed that a major redesign of the 747 wing would be necessary.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Maintaining the same 747 handling characteristics would be important to minimize pilot retraining.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing decided instead to pursue a shortened four-engine 747, resulting in the 747SP.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In January 1986, Boeing outlined preliminary studies to build a larger, ultra-long haul version named the 747-500, which would enter service in the mid- to late-1990s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The aircraft derivative would use engines evolved from unducted fan (UDF) (propfan) technology by General Electric, but the engines would have shrouds, sport a bypass ratio of 15–20, and have a propfan diameter of 10–12 feet (3.0–3.7 m).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing announced the 747 ASB (*Advanced Short Body*) in 1986 as a response to the Airbus A340 and the McDonnell Douglas MD-11.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] This aircraft design would have combined the advanced technology used on the 747-400 with the foreshortened 747SP fuselage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The aircraft was to carry 295 passengers over a range of 8,000 nmi (15,000 km; 9,200 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] However, airlines were not interested in the project and it was canceled later that year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing announced the 747-500X and -600X at the 1996 Farnborough Airshow.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The proposed models would have combined the 747's fuselage with a new wing spanning 251 feet (77 m) derived from the 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Other changes included adding more powerful engines and increasing the number of tires from two to four on the nose landing gear and from 16 to 20 on the main landing gear.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-500X concept featured a fuselage length increased by 18 feet (5.5 m) to 250 feet (76 m), and the aircraft was to carry 462 passengers over a range up to 8,700 nautical miles (16,100 km; 10,000 mi), with a gross weight of over 1.0 Mlb (450 tonnes).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-600X concept featured a greater stretch to 279 feet (85 m) with seating for 548 passengers, a range of up to 7,700 nmi (14,300 km; 8,900 mi), and a gross weight of 1.2 Mlb (540 tonnes).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A third study concept, the 747-700X, would have combined the wing of the 747-600X with a widened fuselage, allowing it to carry 650 passengers over the same range as a 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The cost of the changes from previous 747 models, especially the new wing for the 747-500X and -600X, was estimated to be more than US$5 billion.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Boeing was not able to attract enough interest to launch the aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As Airbus progressed with its A3XX study, Boeing offered a 747 derivative as an alternative in 2000; a more modest proposal than the previous -500X and -600X with the 747's overall wing design and a new segment at the root, increasing the span to 229 ft (69.8 m).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Power would have been supplied by either the Engine Alliance GP7172 or the Rolls-Royce Trent 600, which were also proposed for the 767-400ERX.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A new flight deck based on the 777's would be used.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747X aircraft was to carry 430 passengers over ranges of up to 8,700 nmi (16,100 km; 10,000 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747X Stretch would be extended to 263 ft (80.2 m) long, allowing it to carry 500 passengers over ranges of up to 7,800 nmi (14,400 km; 9,000 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Both would feature an interior based on the 777.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Freighter versions of the 747X and 747X Stretch were also studied.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Like its predecessor, the 747X family was unable to garner enough interest to justify production, and it was shelved along with the 767-400ERX in March 2001, when Boeing announced the Sonic Cruiser concept.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Though the 747X design was less costly than the 747-500X and -600X, it was criticized for not offering a sufficient advance from the existing 747-400.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747X did not make it beyond the drawing board, but the 747-400X being developed concurrently moved into production to become the 747-400ER.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] After the end of the 747X program, Boeing continued to study improvements that could be made to the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747-400XQLR (Quiet Long Range) was meant to have an increased range of 7,980 nmi (14,780 km; 9,180 mi), with improvements to boost efficiency and reduce noise.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Improvements studied included raked wingtips similar to those used on the 767-400ER and a sawtooth engine nacelle for noise reduction.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Although the 747-400XQLR did not move to production, many of its features were used for the 747 Advanced, which was launched as the 747-8 in 2005.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747 was utilized by various airlines from the Asia-Pacific region, the Americas, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Historically, it was the primary long-haul aircraft for operators like Air France, Air New Zealand, British Airways, Cathay Pacific, Japan Airlines, Lufthansa, Northwest Airlines, Pan Am, Qantas, Singapore Airlines, and United Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Qantas notably became the first airline in the world to operate an all-747 fleet after the retirement of its last 707 in 1979.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In 1984, Qantas operated a total of 25 aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The largest all-time operator of the 747 was Japan Airlines, which operated a total of 115 747s comprising 20 -100s, 34 -200s, 16 -300s, and 45 -400s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As of July 2019, there were 462 Boeing 747s in airline service, with Atlas Air and British Airways being the largest operators with 33 747-400s each.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The last US passenger Boeing 747 was retired from Delta Air Lines in December 2017.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The model flew for almost every American major carrier since its 1970 introduction.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Delta flew three of its last four aircraft on a farewell tour, from Seattle to Atlanta on December 19 then to Los Angeles and Minneapolis/St Paul on December 20.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As the IATA forecast an increase in air freight from 4% to 5% in 2018 fueled by booming trade for time-sensitive goods, from smartphones to fresh flowers, demand for freighters is strong while passenger 747s are phased out.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Of the 1,574 produced, 890 are retired; as of 2018, a small subset of those which were intended to be parted-out got $3 million D-checks before flying again.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Young -400s were sold for 320 million yuan ($50 million) and Boeing stopped converting freighters, which used to cost nearly $30 million.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] This comeback helped the airframer financing arm Boeing Capital to shrink its exposure to the 747-8 from $1.07 billion in 2017 to $481 million in 2018.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] In July 2020, British Airways announced that it was retiring its 747 fleet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The final British Airways 747 flights departed London Heathrow on October 8, 2020.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Includes the VC-25A, two heavily modified 747-200Bs used for presidential transport by the U.S.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] All aircraft were later converted to E-4Bs.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] BLCF refers to the 747-400LCF Dreamlifter, used to transport components for the Boeing 787 Dreamliner program.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Orders and deliveries through to the end of February 2023.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] As of November 2023, the 747 has been involved in 173 aviation accidents and incidents, including 65 hull losses (53 in-flight accidents), causing 3,746 fatalities.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] There have been several hijackings of Boeing 747s, such as Pan Am Flight 73, a 747-100 hijacked by four terrorists, resulting in 20 deaths.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The 747 also fell victim to several mid-air bombings, two of which resulted in major fatalities and hull losses, Air India Flight 182 in 1985, and Pan Am Flight 103 in 1988.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The deadliest aviation accident, the Tenerife airport disaster, resulted from pilot error and communications failure, while the Japan Air Lines Flight 123 and China Airlines Flight 611 crashes stemmed from improper aircraft repair due to a tail-strike.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Korean Air Lines Flight 007 was shot down by a Soviet Su-15TM interceptor in 1983 after it had violated Soviet airspace for over 12 minutes, causing US President Ronald Reagan to authorize the then-strictly-military global positioning system (GPS) for civilian use.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] South African Airways Flight 295, a 747-200M Combi, which crashed on 28 November 1987 due to an in-flight fire, led to the mandate of adding fire-suppression systems on board Combi variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] A handful of crashes have been attributed to 747 design flaws, mainly older 747 classic (100/200/300/SP) variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] TWA Flight 800, a 747-100 that exploded in mid-air on July 17, 1996 due to sparking from the old and cracked electrical wires inside the fuel tank, where voltage levels exceeded the maximum limit, causing ignition of the fuel vapors inside the tank.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] This finding led the FAA to adopt a rule in July 2008 requiring installation of an inerting system in the center fuel tank of most large aircraft, after years of research into solutions.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] At the time, the new safety system was expected to cost US$100,000 to $450,000 per aircraft and weigh approximately 200 pounds (91 kg).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Two 747-200F freighters - China Airlines Flight 358 on December 29, 1991, and El Al Flight 1862 on October 4, 1992, crashed after the fuse pins for an engine (no.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] 3) broke off shortly after take-off due to metal fatigue, and instead of simply dropping away from the wing, the engine knocked off the adjacent engine and damaged the wing.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Following these crashes, Boeing issued a directive to examine and replace all fuse pins found to be cracked.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] Other incidents did not result in any hull losses, but the planes suffered certain damages and were put back into service after repair.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] On July 30, 1971, Pan Am Flight 845 struck approach lighting system structures while taking off from San Francisco for Tokyo, Japan; the plane dumped fuel and landed back.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The cause was pilot error with improper calculations, and the plane was repaired and returned to service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] On June 24, 1982, British Airways Flight 9, a Boeing 747-200, registration *G-BDXH*, flew through a cloud of volcanic ash and dust from the eruption of Mount Galunggung, suffering an all engine flameout; the crew restarted the engines and successfully landed at Jakarta.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The volcanic ash caused windscreens to be sandblasted along with engine damage and paint rip-off; the plane was repaired with engines replaced and returned to service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] On December 11, 1994, on board Philippine Airlines Flight 434 from Manila to Tokyo via Cebu, a bomb exploded under a seat, killing one passenger; the plane landed safely at Okinawa despite damage to the plane's controls.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p02] The bomber, Ramzi Yousef, was caught on 7 February 1995 in Islamabad, Pakistan, and the plane was repaired, but converted for cargo use.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] As increasing numbers of "classic" 747-100 and 747-200 series aircraft have been retired, some have been used for other uses such as museum displays.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Some older 747-300s and 747-400s were later added to museum collections.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Upon its retirement from service, the 747 which was number two in the production line was dismantled and shipped to Hopyeong, Namyangju, Gyeonggi-do, South Korea where it was re-assembled, repainted in a livery similar to that of Air Force One and converted into a restaurant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Originally flown commercially by Pan Am as N747PA, *Clipper Juan T.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Trippe*, and repaired for service following a tailstrike, it stayed with the airline until its bankruptcy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The restaurant closed by 2009, and the aircraft was scrapped in 2010.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] A former British Airways 747-200B, G-BDXJ, is parked at the Dunsfold Aerodrome in Surrey, England and has been used as a movie set for productions such as the 2006 James Bond film, *Casino Royale* using the fictional registration N88892 and N9747P.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The airplane also appears frequently in the television series *Top Gear*, which is filmed at Dunsfold.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The *Jumbo Stay* hostel, using a converted 747-200 formerly operated by Singapore Airlines and registered as 9V-SQE, opened at Arlanda Airport, Stockholm in January 2009.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] It closed in March 2025 after the owner declared bankruptcy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] A former Pakistan International Airlines 747-300 was converted into a restaurant by Pakistan's Airports Security Force in 2017.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] It is located at Jinnah International Airport, Karachi.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The wings of a 747 have been repurposed as roofs of a house in Malibu, California.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] In 2023, a Boeing 747-412, retired from Lion Air, was turned into a steak restaurant in Bekasi, Indonesia.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The aircraft had been sitting since 2018 but the construction of the restaurant was delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Two used 747-400s were cannibalized to build the Scaled Composites Stratolaunch aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Following its debut, the 747 rapidly achieved iconic status.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The aircraft entered the cultural lexicon as the original *Jumbo Jet*, a term coined by the aviation media to describe its size, and was also nicknamed *Queen of the Skies*.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Davies described it as "a most impressive aeroplane with a number of exceptionally fine qualities", and praised its flight control system as "truly outstanding" because of its redundancy.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Appearing in over 300 film productions, the 747 is one of the most widely depicted civilian aircraft and is considered by many as one of the most iconic in film history.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] It has appeared in film productions such as the disaster films *Airport 1975* and *Airport '77*, as well as *Air Force One*, *Die Hard 2*, and *Executive Decision*.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] Beyond its media presence, the 747's interior configuration introduced a physical social hierarchy within commercial aviation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] With an increased seating capacity on the lower deck, ticket prices decreased and made long-haul travel more accessible.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] The upper deck promoted luxury, featuring sofas, bars, and premium amenities that began the formalization of the modern business and first-class cabin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-747-p03] This separation of classes established a precedent for class differentiation in the wide-body aircraft design.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The **Boeing 767** is an American wide-body airliner developed and manufactured by Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The airliner design was launched as the 7X7 program on July 14, 1978, the prototype first flew on September 26, 1981, and it was certified on July 30, 1982.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The initial 767-200 variant entered service on September 8, 1982, with United Airlines, and the extended-range 767-200ER in 1984.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] It was stretched into the 767-300 in October 1986, followed by the extended-range 767-300ER in 1988, the most popular variant.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767-300F, a production freighter version, debuted in October 1995.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] It was stretched again into the 767-400ER from September 2000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Designed to complement the larger 747, it has a seven-abreast cross-section accommodating smaller LD2 ULD cargo containers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767 is Boeing's first wide-body twinjet, powered by General Electric CF6, Rolls-Royce RB211, or Pratt & Whitney JT9D turbofans.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] JT9D engines were eventually replaced by PW4000 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The aircraft has a conventional tail and a supercritical wing for reduced aerodynamic drag.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Its two-crew glass cockpit, a first for a Boeing airliner, was developed jointly for the 757 − a narrow-body aircraft, allowing a common pilot type rating.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Studies for a higher-capacity 767 in 1986 led Boeing to develop the larger 777 twinjet, introduced in June 1995.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Military derivatives include the E-767 for surveillance and the KC-767 and KC-46 aerial tankers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Initially marketed for transcontinental routes, a loosening of ETOPS rules starting in 1985 allowed the aircraft to operate transatlantic flights.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] A total of 742 of these aircraft were in service in July 2018, with Delta Air Lines being the largest operator with 77 aircraft in its fleet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] As of May 2026, Boeing has received 1,451 orders from 74 customers, of which 1,362 airplanes have been delivered, while the remaining orders are for cargo or tanker variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Competitors have included the Airbus A300, A310, and A330-200.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Its successor, the 787 Dreamliner, entered service in 2011.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In 1970, the 747 entered service as the first wide-body jetliner with a fuselage wide enough to feature a twin-aisle cabin.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Two years later, the manufacturer began a development study, code-named 7X7, for a new wide-body jetliner intended to replace the 707 and other early generation narrow-body airliners.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The aircraft would also provide twin-aisle seating, but in a smaller fuselage than the existing 747, McDonnell Douglas DC-10, and Lockheed L-1011 TriStar wide-bodies.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] To defray the high cost of development, Boeing signed risk-sharing agreements with Italian corporation Aeritalia and the Civil Transport Development Corporation (CTDC), a consortium of Japanese aerospace companies.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] This marked the manufacturer's first major international joint venture, and both Aeritalia and the CTDC received supply contracts in return for their early participation.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The initial 7X7 was conceived as a short take-off and landing airliner intended for short-distance flights, but customers were unenthusiastic about the concept, leading to its redefinition as a mid-size, transcontinental-range airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] At this stage the proposed aircraft featured two or three engines, with possible configurations including over-wing engines and a T-tail.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] By 1976, a twinjet layout, similar to the one which had debuted on the Airbus A300, became the baseline configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The decision to use two engines reflected increased industry confidence in the reliability and economics of new-generation jet powerplants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] While airline requirements for new wide-body aircraft remained ambiguous, the 7X7 was generally focused on mid-size, high-density markets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] As such, it was intended to transport large numbers of passengers between major cities.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Advancements in civil aerospace technology, including high-bypass-ratio turbofan engines, new flight deck systems, aerodynamic improvements, and more efficient lightweight designs were to be applied to the 7X7.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Many of these features were also included in a parallel development effort for a new mid-size narrow-body airliner, code-named 7N7, which would become the 757.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Work on both proposals proceeded through the airline industry upturn in the late 1970s.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In January 1978, Boeing announced a major extension of its Everett factory—which was then dedicated to manufacturing the 747—to accommodate its new wide-body family.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In February 1978, the new jetliner received the 767 model designation, and three variants were planned: a 767-100 with 190 seats, a 767-200 with 210 seats, and a trijet 767MR/LR version with 200 seats intended for intercontinental routes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767MR/LR was subsequently renamed 777 for differentiation purposes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767 was officially launched on July 14, 1978, when United Airlines ordered 30 of the 767-200 variant, followed by 50 more 767-200 orders from American Airlines and Delta Air Lines later that year.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767-100 was ultimately not offered for sale, as its capacity was too close to the 757's seating, while the 777 trijet was eventually dropped in favor of standardizing the twinjet configuration.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In the late 1970s, operating cost replaced capacity as the primary factor in airliner purchases.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] As a result, the 767's design process emphasized fuel efficiency from the outset.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Boeing targeted a 20 to 30 percent cost saving over earlier aircraft, mainly through new engine and wing technology.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] As development progressed, engineers used computer-aided design for over a third of the 767's design drawings, and performed 26,000 hours of wind tunnel tests.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Design work occurred concurrently with the 757 twinjet, leading Boeing to treat both as almost one program to reduce risk and cost.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Both aircraft would ultimately receive shared design features, including avionics, flight management systems, instruments, and handling characteristics.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Combined development costs were estimated at $3.5 to $4 billion.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Early 767 customers were given the choice of Pratt & Whitney JT9D or General Electric CF6 turbofans, marking the first time that Boeing had offered more than one engine option at the launch of a new airliner.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Both jet engine models had a maximum output of 48,000 pounds-force (210 kN) of thrust.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The engines were mounted approximately one-third the length of the wing from the fuselage, similar to previous wide-body trijets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The larger wings were designed using an aft-loaded shape which reduced aerodynamic drag and distributed lift more evenly across their surface span than any of the manufacturer's previous aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The wings provided higher-altitude cruise performance, added fuel capacity, and expansion room for future stretched variants.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The initial 767-200 was designed for sufficient range to fly across North America or across the northern Atlantic, and would be capable of operating routes up to 3,850 nautical miles (7,130 km; 4,430 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767's fuselage width was set midway between that of the 707 and the 747 at 16.5 feet (5.03 m).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] While it was narrower than previous wide-body designs, seven abreast seating with two aisles could be fitted, and the reduced width produced less aerodynamic drag.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The fuselage was not wide enough to accommodate two standard LD3 wide-body unit load devices side-by-side, so a smaller container, the LD2, was created specifically for the 767.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Using a conventional tail design also allowed the rear fuselage to be tapered over a shorter section, providing for parallel aisles along the full length of the passenger cabin, and eliminating irregular seat rows toward the rear of the aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767 was the first Boeing wide-body to be designed with a two-crew digital glass cockpit.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Cathode ray tube (CRT) color displays and new electronics replaced the role of the flight engineer by enabling the pilot and co-pilot to monitor aircraft systems directly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Despite the promise of reduced crew costs, United Airlines initially demanded a conventional three-person cockpit, citing concerns about the risks associated with introducing a new aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The carrier maintained this position until July 1981, when a US presidential task force determined that a crew of two was safe for operating wide-body jets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] A three-crew cockpit remained as an option and was fitted to the first production models.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Ansett Australia ordered 767s with three-crew cockpits due to union demands; it was the only airline to operate 767s so configured.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767's two-crew cockpit was also applied to the 757, allowing pilots to operate both aircraft after a short conversion course, and adding incentive for airlines to purchase both types.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] To produce the 767, Boeing formed a network of subcontractors which included domestic suppliers and international contributions from Italy's Aeritalia and Japan's CTDC.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The wings and cabin floor were produced in-house, while Aeritalia provided control surfaces, Boeing Vertol made the leading edge for the wings, and Boeing Wichita produced the forward fuselage.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The CTDC provided multiple assemblies through its constituent companies, namely Fuji Heavy Industries (wing fairings and gear doors), Kawasaki Heavy Industries (center fuselage), and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries (rear fuselage, doors, and tail).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Components were integrated during final assembly at the Everett factory.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] For expedited production of wing spars, the main structural member of aircraft wings, the Everett factory received robotic machinery to automate the process of drilling holes and inserting fasteners.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] This method of wing construction expanded on techniques developed for the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Final assembly of the first aircraft began in July 1979.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The prototype aircraft, registered as N767BA and equipped with Pratt & Whitney JT9D turbofans, was rolled out on August 4, 1981.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] By this time, the 767 program had accumulated 173 firm orders from 17 customers, including Air Canada, All Nippon Airways, Britannia Airways, Transbrasil, and Trans World Airlines (TWA).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] On September 26, 1981, the prototype took its maiden flight under the command of company test pilots Tommy Edmonds, Lew Wallick, and John Brit.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The maiden flight was largely uneventful, save for the inability to retract the landing gear because of a hydraulic fluid leak.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The prototype was used for subsequent flight tests.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 10-month 767 flight test program utilized the first six aircraft built.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The first four aircraft were equipped with JT9D engines, while the fifth and sixth were fitted with CF6 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The test fleet was largely used to evaluate avionics, flight systems, handling, and performance, while the sixth aircraft was used for route-proving flights.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] During testing, pilots described the 767 as generally easy to fly, with its maneuverability unencumbered by the bulkiness associated with larger wide-body jets.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Following 1,600 hours of flight tests, the JT9D-powered 767-200 received certification from the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and the UK Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) in July 1982.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The first delivery occurred on August 19, 1982, to United Airlines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The CF6-powered 767-200 received certification in September 1982, followed by the first delivery to Delta Air Lines on October 25, 1982.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767 entered service with United Airlines on September 8, 1982.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The aircraft's first commercial flight used a JT9D-powered 767-200 on the Chicago-to-Denver route.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The CF6-powered 767-200 commenced service three months later with Delta Air Lines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Upon delivery, early 767s were mainly deployed on domestic routes, including US transcontinental services.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] American Airlines and TWA began flying the 767-200 in late 1982, while Air Canada, China Airlines, El Al, and Pacific Western began operating the aircraft in 1983.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The aircraft's introduction was relatively smooth, with few operational glitches and greater dispatch reliability than prior jetliners.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Following the 1996 in-flight explosion of TWA Flight 800, the FAA introduced new rules about flammability reduction in 2008.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In 2012, Boeing requested an exemption for the 767 from new wiring separation rules that would prevent ignition sources, because design improvements it introduced fell short of meeting such rules.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] One of the justification by Boeing: changes to the fuel quantity indication system would require a halt of delivery by three years as production of the 767 model was expected to end shortly.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] FAA gave the manufacturer three years to have a compliant system while deliveries continued.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In 2014, Boeing, without a new design available, asked for and received another time-limited exemption for just the 767-300 and 767-300ER until 2019 when commercial production was expected to cease.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] But in 2017, with continual demand for the 767-300F, Boeing asked for another exemption up to the end of 2027, well past the revised production end date.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Since the 2019 exemption went into effect, Boeing has increased production of the freighter to satisfy demand.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Forecasting airline interest in larger-capacity models, Boeing announced the stretched 767-300 in 1983 and the extended-range 767-300ER in 1984.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Both models offered a 20 percent passenger capacity increase, while the extended-range version was capable of operating flights up to 5,990 nautical miles (11,090 km; 6,890 mi).
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Japan Airlines placed the first order for the -300 in September 1983.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Following its first flight on January 30, 1986, the type entered service with Japan Airlines on October 20, 1986.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767-300ER completed its first flight on December 9, 1986, but it was not until March 1987 that the first firm order, from American Airlines, was placed.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The type entered service with American Airlines on March 3, 1988.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767-300 and 767-300ER gained popularity after entering service, and came to account for approximately two-thirds of all 767s sold.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Until the 777's 1995 debut, the 767-300 and 767-300ER remained Boeing's second-largest wide-bodies behind the 747.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Buoyed by a recovering global economy and ETOPS approval, 767 sales accelerated in the mid-to-late 1980s; 1989 was the most prolific year with 132 firm orders.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] By the early 1990s, the wide-body twinjet had become its manufacturer's annual best-selling aircraft, despite a slight decrease due to economic recession.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] During this period, the 767 became the most common airliner for transatlantic flights between North America and Europe.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] By the end of the decade, 767s crossed the Atlantic more frequently than all other aircraft types combined.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767 also propelled the growth of point-to-point flights which bypassed major airline hubs in favor of direct routes.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Taking advantage of the aircraft's lower operating costs and smaller capacity, operators added non-stop flights to secondary population centers, thereby eliminating the need for connecting flights.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The increased number of cities receiving non-stop services caused a paradigm shift in the airline industry as point-to-point travel gained prominence at the expense of the traditional hub-and-spoke model.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In February 1990, the first 767 equipped with Rolls-Royce RB211 turbofans, a 767-300, was delivered to British Airways.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Six months later, the carrier temporarily grounded its entire 767 fleet after discovering cracks in the engine pylons of several aircraft.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The cracks were related to the extra weight of the RB211 engines, which are 2,205 pounds (1,000 kg) heavier than other 767 engines.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] During the grounding, interim repairs were conducted to alleviate stress on engine pylon components, and a parts redesign in 1991 prevented further cracks.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Boeing also performed a structural reassessment, resulting in production changes and modifications to the engine pylons of all 767s in service.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In January 1993, following an order from UPS Airlines, Boeing launched a freighter variant, the 767-300F, which entered service with UPS on October 16, 1995.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The 767-300F featured a main deck cargo hold, upgraded landing gear, and strengthened wing structure.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In November 1993, the Japanese government launched the first 767 military derivative when it placed orders for the E-767, an Airborne Early Warning and Control (AWACS) variant based on the 767-200ER.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The first two E-767s, featuring extensive modifications to accommodate surveillance radar and other monitoring equipment, were delivered in 1998 to the Japan Self-Defense Forces.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In November 1995, after abandoning development of a smaller version of the 777, Boeing announced that it was revisiting studies for a larger 767.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The proposed 767-400X, a second stretch of the aircraft, offered a 12 percent capacity increase versus the 767-300, and featured an upgraded flight deck, enhanced interior, and greater wingspan.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The variant was specifically aimed at Delta Air Lines' pending replacement of its aging Lockheed L-1011 TriStars, and faced competition from the A330-200, a shortened derivative of the Airbus A330.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In March 1997, Delta Air Lines launched the 767-400ER when it ordered the type to replace its L-1011 fleet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In October 1997, Continental Airlines also ordered the 767-400ER to replace its McDonnell Douglas DC-10 fleet.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The type completed its first flight on October 9, 1999, and entered service with Continental Airlines on September 14, 2000.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In the early 2000s, cumulative 767 deliveries approached 900, but new sales declined during an airline industry downturn.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In 2001, Boeing dropped plans for a longer-range model, the 767-400ERX, in favor of the proposed Sonic Cruiser, a new jetliner which aimed to fly 15 percent faster while having comparable fuel costs to the 767.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The following year, Boeing announced the KC-767 Tanker Transport, a second military derivative of the 767-200ER.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Launched with an order in October 2002 from the Italian Air Force, the KC-767 was intended for the dual role of refueling other aircraft and carrying cargo.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The Japanese government became the second customer for the type in March 2003.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In May 2003, the United States Air Force (USAF) announced its intent to lease KC-767s to replace its aging KC-135 tankers.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The plan was suspended in March 2004 amid a conflict of interest scandal, resulting in multiple US government investigations and the departure of several Boeing officials, including Philip Condit, the company's chief executive officer, and chief financial officer Michael Sears.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The first KC-767s were delivered in 2008 to the Japan Self-Defense Forces.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] In late 2002, after airlines expressed reservations about its emphasis on speed over cost reduction, Boeing halted development of the Sonic Cruiser.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The following year, the manufacturer announced the 7E7, a mid-size 767 successor made from composite materials which promised to be 20 percent more fuel efficient.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] The new jetliner was the first stage of a replacement aircraft initiative called the Boeing Yellowstone Project.
[src:overall-pressure-ratio/boeing-767-p01] Customers embraced the 7E7, later renamed 787 Dreamliner, and within two years it had become the fastest-selling airliner in the company's history.
